[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] The theorem is sometimes called **Sunzi's theorem**.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] Both names of the theorem refer to its earliest known statement that appeared in *Sunzi Suanjing*, a Chinese manuscript written during the 3rd to 5th century CE.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] If one knows that the remainder of *n* divided by 3 is 2, the remainder of *n* divided by 5 is 3, and the remainder of *n* divided by 7 is 2, then with no other information, one can determine the remainder of *n* divided by 105 (the product of 3, 5, and 7) without knowing the value of *n*.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] Moreover, this remainder is the only possible positive value of *n* that is less than 105.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] The Chinese remainder theorem is widely used for computing with large integers, as it allows replacing a computation for which one knows a bound on the size of the result by several similar computations on small integers.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] The Chinese remainder theorem (expressed in terms of congruences) is true over every principal ideal domain.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] It has been generalized to any ring, with a formulation involving two-sided ideals.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] Sunzi's work would not be considered a theorem by modern standards; it only gives one particular problem, without showing how to solve it, much less any proof about the general case or a general algorithm for solving it.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] An algorithm for solving this problem was described by Aryabhata (6th century).
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] Special cases of the Chinese remainder theorem were also known to Brahmagupta (7th century) and appear in Fibonacci's Liber Abaci (1202).
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] The result was later generalized with a complete solution called *Da-yan-shu* (大衍術) in Qin Jiushao's 1247 *Mathematical Treatise in Nine Sections* which was translated into English in early 19th century by British missionary Alexander Wylie.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] The notion of congruences was first introduced and used by Carl Friedrich Gauss in his *Disquisitiones Arithmeticae* of 1801.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] Let *n*1, ..., *n**k* be integers greater than 1, which are often called *moduli* or *divisors*.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] Let us denote by *N* the product of the *n**i*.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] has a solution, and any two solutions, say *x*1 and *x*2, are congruent modulo *N*, that is, *x*1 ≡ *x*2 (mod *N* ).
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] between the ring of integers modulo *N* and the direct product of the rings of integers modulo the *n**i*.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] This means that for doing a sequence of arithmetic operations in $\mathbb {Z} /N\mathbb {Z} ,$ one may do the same computation independently in each $\mathbb {Z} /n_{i}\mathbb {Z}$ and then get the result by applying the isomorphism (from the right to the left).
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] This may be much faster than the direct computation if *N* and the number of operations are large.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] This is widely used, under the name *multi-modular computation*, for linear algebra over the integers or the rational numbers.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] The theorem can also be restated in the language of combinatorics as the fact that the infinite arithmetic progressions of integers form a Helly family.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] The existence and the uniqueness of the solution may be proven independently.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] However, the first proof of existence, given below, uses this uniqueness.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] Suppose that x and y are both solutions to all the congruences.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] As x and y give the same remainder, when divided by *ni*, their difference *x* − *y* is a multiple of each *ni*.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] As the *ni* are pairwise coprime, their product *N* also divides *x* − *y*, and thus x and y are congruent modulo *N*.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] If x and y are supposed to be non-negative and less than *N* (as in the first statement of the theorem), then their difference may be a multiple of *N* only if *x* = *y*.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] maps congruence classes modulo *N* to sequences of congruence classes modulo *ni*.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] The proof of uniqueness shows that this map is injective.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] As the domain and the codomain of this map have the same number of elements, the map is also surjective, which proves the existence of the solution.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] This proof is very simple but does not provide any direct way for computing a solution.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] Moreover, it cannot be generalized to other situations where the following proof can.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] Existence may be established by an explicit construction of x.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] This construction may be split into two steps, first solving the problem in the case of two moduli, and then extending this solution to the general case by induction on the number of moduli.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] The integers $m_{1}$ and $m_{2}$ may be computed by the extended Euclidean algorithm.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] implying that $x\equiv a_{1}{\pmod {n_{1}}}.$ The second congruence is proved similarly, by exchanging the subscripts 1 and 2.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] The two first equations have a solution $a_{1,2}$ provided by the method of the previous section.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] As the other $n_{i}$ are coprime with $n_{1}n_{2},$ this reduces solving the initial problem of k equations to a similar problem with $k-1$ equations.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] Iterating the process, one gets eventually the solutions of the initial problem.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] For constructing a solution, it is not necessary to make an induction on the number of moduli.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] However, such a direct construction involves more computation with large numbers, which makes it less efficient and less used.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] Nevertheless, Lagrange interpolation is a special case of this construction, applied to polynomials instead of integers.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] Let $N_{i}=N/n_{i}$ be the product of all moduli but one.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] As the $n_{i}$ are pairwise coprime, $N_{i}$ and $n_{i}$ are coprime.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] Several methods of computation are presented.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] The two first ones are useful for small examples, but become very inefficient when the product $n_{1}\cdots n_{k}$ is large.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] The third one uses the existence proof given in § Existence (constructive proof).
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] It is the most convenient when the product $n_{1}\cdots n_{k}$ is large, or for computer computation.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] It is easy to check whether a value of x is a solution: it suffices to compute the remainder of the Euclidean division of x by each *n**i*.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] Thus, to find the solution, it suffices to check successively the integers from 0 to N until finding the solution.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] Although very simple, this method is very inefficient.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] For the simple example considered here, 40 integers (including 0) have to be checked for finding the solution, which is 39.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] This is an exponential time algorithm, as the size of the input is, up to a constant factor, the number of digits of N, and the average number of operations is of the order of N.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] Therefore, this method is rarely used, neither for hand-written computation nor on computers.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] The search of the solution may be made dramatically faster by sieving.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] For this method, we suppose, without loss of generality, that $0\leq a_{i}<n_{i}$ (if it were not the case, it would suffice to replace each $a_{i}$ by the remainder of its division by $n_{i}$ ).
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] By testing the values of these numbers modulo $n_{2},$ one eventually finds a solution $x_{2}$ of the two first congruences.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] Testing the values of these numbers modulo $n_{3},$ and continuing until every modulus has been tested eventually yields the solution.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] This method is faster if the moduli have been ordered by decreasing value, that is if $n_{1}>n_{2}>\cdots >n_{k}.$ For the example, this gives the following computation.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] We consider first the numbers that are congruent to 4 modulo 5 (the largest modulus), which are 4, 9 = 4 + 5, 14 = 9 + 5, ...
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] For each of them, compute the remainder by 4 (the second largest modulus) until getting a number congruent to 3 modulo 4.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] Then one can proceed by adding 20 = 5 × 4 at each step, and computing only the remainders by 3.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] This method works well for hand-written computation with a product of moduli that is not too big.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] However, it is much slower than other methods, for very large products of moduli.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] Although dramatically faster than the systematic search, this method also has an exponential time complexity and is therefore not used on computers.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] For more than two moduli, the method for two moduli allows the replacement of any two congruences by a single congruence modulo the product of the moduli.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] Iterating this process provides eventually the solution with a complexity, which is quadratic in the number of digits of the product of all moduli.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] This quadratic time complexity does not depend on the order in which the moduli are regrouped.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] One may regroup the two first moduli, then regroup the resulting modulus with the next one, and so on.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] This strategy is the easiest to implement, but it also requires more computation involving large numbers.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] Another strategy consists in partitioning the moduli in pairs whose product have comparable sizes (as much as possible), applying, in parallel, the method of two moduli to each pair, and iterating with a number of moduli approximatively divided by two.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] This method allows an easy parallelization of the algorithm.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] Also, if fast algorithms (that is, algorithms working in quasilinear time) are used for the basic operations, this method provides an algorithm for the whole computation that works in quasilinear time.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] On the current example (which has only three moduli), both strategies are identical and work as follows.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] for a solution of the two first congruences, the other solutions being obtained by adding to −9 any multiple of 3 × 4 = 12.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] The other solutions are obtained by adding any multiple of 3 × 4 × 5 = 60, and the smallest positive solution is −21 + 60 = 39.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] where the unknown integers are x and the $x_{i}.$ Therefore, every general method for solving such systems may be used for finding the solution of Chinese remainder theorem, such as the reduction of the matrix of the system to Smith normal form or Hermite normal form.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] However, as usual when using a general algorithm for a more specific problem, this approach is less efficient than the method of the preceding section, based on a direct use of Bézout's identity.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] In § Statement, the Chinese remainder theorem has been stated in three different ways: in terms of remainders, of congruences, and of a ring isomorphism.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] The statement in terms of remainders does not apply, in general, to principal ideal domains, as remainders are not defined in such rings.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] However, the two other versions make sense over a principal ideal domain *R*: it suffices to replace "integer" by "element of the domain" and $\mathbb {Z}$ by *R*.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] These two versions of the theorem are true in this context, because the proofs (except for the first existence proof), are based on Euclid's lemma and Bézout's identity, which are true over every principal domain.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] However, in general, the theorem is only an existence theorem and does not provide any way for computing the solution, unless one has an algorithm for computing the coefficients of Bézout's identity.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] The statement in terms of remainders given in § Theorem statement cannot be generalized to any principal ideal domain, but its generalization to Euclidean domains is straightforward.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] The univariate polynomials over a field is the typical example of a Euclidean domain which is not the integers.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] Therefore, we state the theorem for the case of the ring $R=K[X]$ for a field $K.$ For getting the theorem for a general Euclidean domain, it suffices to replace the degree by the Euclidean function of the Euclidean domain.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] The Chinese remainder theorem for polynomials is thus: Let $P_{i}(X)$ (the moduli) be, for $i=1,\dots ,k$ , pairwise coprime polynomials in $R=K[X]$ .
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] The construction of the solution may be done as in § Existence (constructive proof) or § Existence (direct proof).
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] However, the latter construction may be simplified by using, as follows, partial fraction decomposition instead of the extended Euclidean algorithm.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] A special case of Chinese remainder theorem for polynomials is Lagrange interpolation.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] They are pairwise coprime if the $x_{i}$ are all different.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] The remainder of the division by $P_{i}(X)$ of a polynomial $P(X)$ is $P(x_{i})$ , by the polynomial remainder theorem.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] Lagrange interpolation formula is exactly the result, in this case, of the above construction of the solution.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] Hermite interpolation is an application of the Chinese remainder theorem for univariate polynomials, which may involve moduli of arbitrary degrees (Lagrange interpolation involves only moduli of degree one).
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] The problem consists of finding a polynomial of the least possible degree, such that the polynomial and its first derivatives take given values at some fixed points.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] therefore $P_{i}(X)$ is its Taylor polynomial of order $r_{i}-1$ at $x_{i}$ , that is, $P(X)$ solves the initial Hermite interpolation problem.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] The Chinese remainder theorem asserts that there exists exactly one polynomial of degree less than the sum of the $r_{i},$ which satisfies these k congruences.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] There are several ways for computing the solution $P(X).$ One may use the method described at the beginning of § Over univariate polynomial rings and Euclidean domains.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] One may also use the constructions given in § Existence (constructive proof) or § Existence (direct proof).
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] The Chinese remainder theorem can be generalized to non-coprime moduli.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] When this condition is satisfied, the set of solutions forms a single congruence class modulo $N={\text{lcm}}(n_{1},\dots ,n_{k}).$ That is, any two solutions differ by a multiple of N , and adding a multiple of N to a solution gives another solution.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] If $a\equiv b{\pmod {g}}$ , then this system has a unique solution modulo $M=mn/g$ .
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] This defines an integer, as g divides both m and n.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] The Chinese remainder theorem can be generalized to any ring, by using coprime ideals (also called comaximal ideals).
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] Two ideals I and J are coprime if there are elements $i\in I$ and $j\in J$ such that $i+j=1.$ This relation plays the role of Bézout's identity in the proofs related to this generalization, which otherwise are very similar.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] The generalization may be stated as follows.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] Let *I*1, ..., *Ik* be two-sided ideals of a ring R and let *I* be their intersection.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] if Ii and Ij are coprime for all *i* ≠ *j*.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] The $e_{i}$ are central idempotents that are pairwise orthogonal; this means, in particular, that $e_{i}^{2}=e_{i}$ and $e_{i}e_{j}=e_{j}e_{i}=0$ for every i and j.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] In summary, this generalized Chinese remainder theorem is the equivalence between giving pairwise coprime two-sided ideals with a zero intersection, and giving central and pairwise orthogonal idempotents that sum to 1.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] The Chinese remainder theorem has been used to construct a Gödel numbering for sequences, which is involved in the proof of Gödel's incompleteness theorems.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] Most implementations of RSA use the Chinese remainder theorem during signing of HTTPS certificates and during decryption.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] The Chinese remainder theorem can also be used in secret sharing, which consists of distributing a set of shares among a group of people who, all together (but no one alone), can recover a certain secret from the given set of shares.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] Each of the shares is represented in a congruence, and the solution of the system of congruences using the Chinese remainder theorem is the secret to be recovered.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] Secret sharing using the Chinese remainder theorem uses, along with the Chinese remainder theorem, special sequences of integers that guarantee the impossibility of recovering the secret from a set of shares with less than a certain cardinality.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] The range ambiguity resolution techniques used with medium pulse repetition frequency radar can be seen as a special case of the Chinese remainder theorem.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] Given a surjection $\mathbb {Z} /n\to \mathbb {Z} /m$ of finite abelian groups, we can use the Chinese remainder theorem to give a complete description of any such map.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] These observations are pivotal for constructing the ring of profinite integers, which is given as an inverse limit of all such maps.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] Otherwise *fi* and *fj* would also be proportional, and thus equal since as monoid homomorphisms they satisfy: *fi* (1) = 1 = *fj* (1), which contradicts the assumption that they are distinct.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] Therefore, the kernels Ker *Fi* and Ker *Fj* are distinct.
[src:number-theory/chinese-remainder-theorem] Because they are distinct and maximal the ideals Ker *Fi* and Ker *Fj* are coprime whenever *i* ≠ *j*.
