[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] In mathematics, the **Euclidean algorithm**, or **Euclid's algorithm**, is an efficient method for computing the greatest common divisor (GCD) of two integers, the largest number that divides them both without a remainder.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] It is named after the ancient Greek mathematician Euclid, who first described it in his *Elements* (c.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] It is an example of an *algorithm*, and is one of the oldest algorithms in common use.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] It can be used to reduce fractions to their simplest form, and is a part of many other number-theoretic and cryptographic calculations.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The Euclidean algorithm is based on the principle that the greatest common divisor of two numbers does not change if the larger number is replaced by its difference with the smaller number.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Since this replacement reduces the larger of the two numbers, repeating this process gives successively smaller pairs of numbers until the two numbers become equal.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] When that occurs, that number is the GCD of the original two numbers.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] By reversing the steps or using the extended Euclidean algorithm, the GCD can be expressed as a linear combination of the two original numbers, that is the sum of the two numbers, each multiplied by an integer (for example, 21 = 5 × 105 + (−2) × 252).
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The fact that the GCD can always be expressed in this way is known as Bézout's identity.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The version of the Euclidean algorithm described above—which follows Euclid's original presentation—may require many subtraction steps to find the GCD when one of the given numbers is much bigger than the other.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] A more efficient version of the algorithm shortcuts these steps, instead replacing the larger of the two numbers by its remainder when divided by the smaller of the two (with this version, the algorithm stops when reaching a zero remainder).
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] With this improvement, the algorithm never requires more steps than five times the number of digits (base 10) of the smaller integer.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] This was proven by Gabriel Lamé in 1844 (Lamé's Theorem), and marks the beginning of computational complexity theory.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Additional methods for improving the algorithm's efficiency were developed in the 20th century.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The Euclidean algorithm has many theoretical and practical applications.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] It is used for reducing fractions to their simplest form and for performing division in modular arithmetic.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Computations using this algorithm form part of the cryptographic protocols that are used to secure internet communications, and in methods for breaking these cryptosystems by factoring large composite numbers.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The Euclidean algorithm may be used to solve Diophantine equations, such as finding numbers that satisfy multiple congruences according to the Chinese remainder theorem, to construct continued fractions, and to find accurate rational approximations to real numbers.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Finally, it can be used as a basic tool for proving theorems in number theory such as Lagrange's four-square theorem and the uniqueness of prime factorizations.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The original algorithm was described only for natural numbers and geometric lengths (real numbers), but the algorithm was generalized in the 19th century to other types of numbers, such as Gaussian integers and polynomials of one variable.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] This led to modern abstract algebraic notions such as Euclidean domains.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The Euclidean algorithm calculates the greatest common divisor (GCD) of two natural numbers a and b.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The greatest common divisor g is the largest natural number that divides both a and b without leaving a remainder.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Synonyms for GCD include *greatest common factor* (GCF), *highest common factor* (HCF), *highest common divisor* (HCD), and *greatest common measure* (GCM).
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The greatest common divisor is often written as gcd(*a*, *b*) or, more simply, as (*a*, *b*), although the latter notation is ambiguous, also used for concepts such as an ideal in the ring of integers, which is closely related to GCD.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] If gcd(*a*, *b*) = 1, then a and b are said to be coprime (or relatively prime).
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] This property does not imply that a or b are themselves prime numbers.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] For example, 6 and 35 factor as 6 = 2 × 3 and 35 = 5 × 7, so they are not prime, but their prime factors are different, so 6 and 35 are coprime, with no common factors other than 1.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Since a and b are both multiples of g, they can be written *a* = *mg* and *b* = *ng*, and there is no larger number *G* > *g* for which this is true.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The natural numbers m and n must be coprime, since any common factor could be factored out of m and n to make g greater.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Thus, any other number c that divides both a and b must also divide g.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The greatest common divisor g of a and b is the unique (positive) common divisor of a and b that is divisible by any other common divisor c.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The greatest common divisor can be visualized as follows.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Consider a rectangular area a by b, and any common divisor c that divides both a and b exactly.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The sides of the rectangle can be divided into segments of length c, which divides the rectangle into a grid of squares of side length c.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The GCD g is the largest value of c for which this is possible.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] For illustration, a 24×60 rectangular area can be divided into a grid of: 1×1 squares, 2×2 squares, 3×3 squares, 4×4 squares, 6×6 squares or 12×12 squares.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] A 24×60 rectangular area can be divided into a grid of 12×12 squares, with two squares along one edge (24/12 = 2) and five squares along the other (60/12 = 5).
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The greatest common divisor of two numbers a and b is the product of the prime factors shared by the two numbers, where each prime factor can be repeated as many times as it divides both a and b.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] For example, since 1386 can be factored into 2 × 3 × 3 × 7 × 11, and 3213 can be factored into 3 × 3 × 3 × 7 × 17, the GCD of 1386 and 3213 equals 63 = 3 × 3 × 7, the product of their shared prime factors (with 3 repeated since 3 × 3 divides both).
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] If two numbers have no common prime factors, their GCD is 1 (obtained here as an instance of the empty product); in other words, they are coprime.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] A key advantage of the Euclidean algorithm is that it can find the GCD efficiently without having to compute the prime factors.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Factorization of large integers is believed to be a computationally very difficult problem, and the security of many widely used cryptographic protocols is based upon its infeasibility.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Another definition of the GCD is helpful in advanced mathematics, particularly ring theory.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The greatest common divisor g of two nonzero numbers a and b is also their smallest positive integral linear combination, that is, the smallest positive number of the form *ua* + *vb* where u and v are integers.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The set of all integral linear combinations of a and b is actually the same as the set of all multiples of g (mg, where m is an integer).
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] In modern mathematical language, the ideal generated by a and b is the ideal generated by g alone (an ideal generated by a single element is called a principal ideal, and all ideals of the integers are principal ideals).
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Some properties of the GCD are in fact easier to see with this description, for instance the fact that any common divisor of a and b also divides the GCD (it divides both terms of *ua* + *vb*).
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The equivalence of this GCD definition with the other definitions is described below.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The GCD of three or more numbers equals the product of the prime factors common to all the numbers, but it can also be calculated by repeatedly taking the GCDs of pairs of numbers.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Thus, Euclid's algorithm, which computes the GCD of two integers, suffices to calculate the GCD of arbitrarily many integers.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Because the sequence of non-negative integers $\{r_{k}\}$ is strictly decreasing, it eventually must terminate.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] In other words, since $r_{k}\geq 0$ for every $k,$ and each $r_{k}$ is an integer that is strictly smaller than the preceding $r_{k-1},$ there eventually cannot be a non-negative integer smaller than zero, and hence the algorithm must terminate.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] In fact, the algorithm will always terminate at the *n*th step with $r_{n}$ equal to zero.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] To illustrate, suppose the GCD of 1071 and 462 is requested.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Therefore, dropping any ordering between the first two integers does not affect the conclusion that the sequence must eventually terminate because the next remainder will always satisfy $r_{0}<b$ and everything continues as above.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The only modifications that need to be made are that $r_{k}<r_{k-1}$ only for $k\geq 0,$ and that the sub-sequence of non-negative integers $\{r_{k-1}\}$ for $k\geq 0$ is strictly decreasing, therefore excluding $a=r_{-2}$ from both statements.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The existence of a step N such that $r_{N}=0$ follows from the condition $|r_{i}|<|r_{i-1}|$ , for $i\geq 1$ .
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] This ensures that the algorithm terminates.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] In particular, the largest of their common divisors are the same.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Property 2 shows that the $\gcd$ of the pairs remains invariant.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] In particular, the $\gcd$ of the first pair $(a,b)$ and the last pair $(r_{N-1},0)$ are the same.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] For illustration, the Euclidean algorithm can be used to find the greatest common divisor of *a* = 1071 and *b* = 462.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] To begin, multiples of 462 are subtracted from 1071 until the remainder is less than 462.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Then multiples of 147 are subtracted from 462 until the remainder is less than 147.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Then multiples of 21 are subtracted from 147 until the remainder is less than 21.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Since the last remainder is zero, the algorithm ends with 21 as the greatest common divisor of 1071 and 462.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] This agrees with the gcd(1071, 462) found by prime factorization above.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The Euclidean algorithm can be visualized in terms of the tiling analogy given above for the greatest common divisor.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Assume that we wish to cover an *a*×*b* rectangle with square tiles exactly, where *a* is the larger of the two numbers.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] We first attempt to tile the rectangle using *b*×*b* square tiles; however, this leaves an *r*0×*b* residual rectangle untiled, where *r*0 < *b*.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] We then attempt to tile the residual rectangle with *r*0×*r*0 square tiles.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] This leaves a second residual rectangle *r*1×*r*0, which we attempt to tile using *r*1×*r*1 square tiles, and so on.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The sequence ends when there is no residual rectangle, i.e., when the square tiles cover the previous residual rectangle exactly.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The length of the sides of the smallest square tile is the GCD of the dimensions of the original rectangle.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] For example, the smallest square tile in the adjacent figure is 21×21 (shown in red), and 21 is the GCD of 1071 and 462, the dimensions of the original rectangle (shown in green).
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] where the *r**k* is non-negative and is strictly less than the absolute value of *r**k*−1.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The theorem which underlies the definition of the Euclidean division ensures that such a quotient and remainder always exist and are unique.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] In Euclid's original version of the algorithm, the quotient and remainder are found by repeated subtraction; that is, *r**k*−1 is subtracted from *r**k*−2 repeatedly until the remainder *r**k* is smaller than *r**k*−1.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] After that *r**k* and *r**k*−1 are exchanged and the process is iterated.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Euclidean division reduces all the steps between two exchanges into a single step, which is thus more efficient.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Moreover, the quotients are not needed, thus one may replace Euclidean division by the modulo operation, which gives only the remainder.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Implementations of the algorithm may be expressed in pseudocode.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] At the beginning of the *k*th iteration, the variable *b* holds the latest remainder *r**k*−1, whereas the variable *a* holds its predecessor, *r**k*−2.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The step *b* := *a* mod *b* is equivalent to the above recursion formula *r**k* ≡ *r**k*−2 mod *r**k*−1.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The temporary variable *t* holds the value of *r**k*−1 while the next remainder *r**k* is being calculated.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] At the end of the loop iteration, the variable *b* holds the remainder *r**k*, whereas the variable *a* holds its predecessor, *r**k*−1.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] In the subtraction-based version, which was Euclid's original version, the remainder calculation (`b := a **mod** b`) is replaced by repeated subtraction.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The variables *a* and *b* alternate holding the previous remainders *r**k*−1 and *r**k*−2.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Assume that *a* is larger than *b* at the beginning of an iteration; then *a* equals *r**k*−2, since *r**k*−2 > *r**k*−1.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] During the loop iteration, *a* is reduced by multiples of the previous remainder *b* until *a* is smaller than *b*.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Then *b* is reduced by multiples of *a* until it is again smaller than *a*, giving the next remainder *r**k*+1, and so on.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The recursive version is based on the equality of the GCDs of successive remainders and the stopping condition gcd(*r**N*−1, 0) = *r**N*−1.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] In another version of Euclid's algorithm, the quotient at each step is increased by one if the resulting negative remainder is smaller in magnitude than the typical positive remainder.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Leopold Kronecker has shown that this version requires the fewest steps of any version of Euclid's algorithm.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] More generally, it has been proven that, for every input numbers *a* and *b*, the number of steps is minimal if and only if *q**k* is chosen in order that $\left|{\frac {r_{k+1}}{r_{k}}}\right|<{\frac {1}{\varphi }}\sim 0.618,$ where $\varphi$ is the golden ratio.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The Euclidean algorithm is one of the oldest algorithms in common use.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] 300 BC), specifically in Book 7 (Propositions 1–2) and Book 10 (Propositions 2–3).
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] In Book 7, the algorithm is formulated for integers, whereas in Book 10, it is formulated for lengths of line segments.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] (In modern usage, one would say it was formulated there for real numbers.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] But lengths, areas, and volumes, represented as real numbers in modern usage, are not measured in the same units and there is no natural unit of length, area, or volume; the concept of real numbers was unknown at that time.) The latter algorithm is geometrical.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The GCD of two lengths *a* and *b* corresponds to the greatest length *g* that measures *a* and *b* evenly; in other words, the lengths *a* and *b* are both integer multiples of the length *g*.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The algorithm was probably not discovered by Euclid, who compiled results from earlier mathematicians in his *Elements*.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] L. van der Waerden suggests that Book VII derives from a textbook on number theory written by mathematicians in the school of Pythagoras.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The algorithm was probably known by Eudoxus of Cnidus (about 375 BC).
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The algorithm may even pre-date Eudoxus, judging from the use of the technical term ἀνθυφαίρεσις (*anthyphairesis*, reciprocal subtraction) in works by Euclid and Aristotle.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Claude Brezinski, following remarks by Pappus of Alexandria, credits the algorithm to Theaetetus (c.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Centuries later, Euclid's algorithm was discovered independently both in India and in China, primarily to solve Diophantine equations that arose in astronomy and making accurate calendars.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] In the late 5th century, the Indian mathematician and astronomer Aryabhata described the algorithm as the "pulverizer", perhaps because of its effectiveness in solving Diophantine equations.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Although a special case of the Chinese remainder theorem had already been described in the Chinese book *Sunzi Suanjing*, the general solution was published by Qin Jiushao in his 1247 book *Shushu Jiuzhang* (數書九章 *Mathematical Treatise in Nine Sections*).
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The Euclidean algorithm was first described *numerically* and popularized in Europe in the second edition of Bachet's *Problèmes plaisants et délectables* (*Pleasant and enjoyable problems*, 1624).
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] In Europe, it was likewise used to solve Diophantine equations and in developing continued fractions.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The extended Euclidean algorithm was published by the English mathematician Nicholas Saunderson, who attributed it to Roger Cotes as a method for computing continued fractions efficiently.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] In the 19th century, the Euclidean algorithm led to the development of new number systems, such as Gaussian integers and Eisenstein integers.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] In 1815, Carl Gauss used the Euclidean algorithm to demonstrate unique factorization of Gaussian integers, although his work was first published in 1832.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Gauss mentioned the algorithm in his *Disquisitiones Arithmeticae* (published 1801), but only as a method for continued fractions.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Peter Gustav Lejeune Dirichlet seems to have been the first to describe the Euclidean algorithm as the basis for much of number theory.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Lejeune Dirichlet noted that many results of number theory, such as unique factorization, would hold true for any other system of numbers to which the Euclidean algorithm could be applied.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Lejeune Dirichlet's lectures on number theory were edited and extended by Richard Dedekind, who used Euclid's algorithm to study algebraic integers, a new general type of number.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] For example, Dedekind was the first to prove Fermat's two-square theorem using the unique factorization of Gaussian integers.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Dedekind also defined the concept of a Euclidean domain, a number system in which a generalized version of the Euclidean algorithm can be defined (as described below).
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] In the closing decades of the 19th century, the Euclidean algorithm gradually became eclipsed by Dedekind's more general theory of ideals.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Other applications of Euclid's algorithm were developed in the 19th century.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] In 1829, Charles Sturm showed that the algorithm was useful in the Sturm chain method for counting the real roots of polynomials in any given interval.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The Euclidean algorithm was the first integer relation algorithm, which is a method for finding integer relations between commensurate real numbers.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Several novel integer relation algorithms have been developed, such as the algorithm of Helaman Ferguson and R.W.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] In 1969, Cole and Davie developed a two-player game based on the Euclidean algorithm, called *The Game of Euclid*, which has an optimal strategy.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The players begin with two piles of *a* and *b* stones.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The players take turns removing *m* multiples of the smaller pile from the larger.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Thus, if the two piles consist of *x* and *y* stones, where *x* is larger than *y*, the next player can reduce the larger pile from *x* stones to *x* − *my* stones, as long as the latter is a nonnegative integer.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The winner is the first player to reduce one pile to zero stones.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Bézout's identity states that the greatest common divisor *g* of two integers *a* and *b* can be represented as a linear sum of the original two numbers *a* and *b*.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] In other words, it is always possible to find integers *s* and *t* such that *g* = *sa* + *tb*.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The integers *s* and *t* can be calculated from the quotients *q*0, *q*1, etc. by reversing the order of equations in Euclid's algorithm.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Substituting these formulae for *r**N*−2 and *r**N*−3 into the first equation yields *g* as a linear sum of the remainders *r**N*−4 and *r**N*−5.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] After all the remainders *r*0, *r*1, etc. have been substituted, the final equation expresses *g* as a linear sum of *a* and *b*, so that *g* = *sa* + *tb*.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The Euclidean algorithm, and thus Bézout's identity, can be generalized to the context of Euclidean domains.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Bézout's identity provides yet another definition of the greatest common divisor *g* of two numbers *a* and *b*.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Consider the set of all numbers *ua* + *vb*, where *u* and *v* are any two integers.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Since *a* and *b* are both divisible by *g*, every number in the set is divisible by *g*.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] In other words, every number of the set is an integer multiple of *g*.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] This is true for every common divisor of *a* and *b*.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] However, unlike other common divisors, the greatest common divisor is a member of the set; by Bézout's identity, choosing *u* = *s* and *v* = *t* gives *g*.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] A smaller common divisor cannot be a member of the set, since every member of the set must be divisible by *g*.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Conversely, any multiple *m* of *g* can be obtained by choosing *u* = *ms* and *v* = *mt*, where *s* and *t* are the integers of Bézout's identity.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Therefore, the set of all numbers *ua* + *vb* is equivalent to the set of multiples *m* of *g*.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] In other words, the set of all possible sums of integer multiples of two numbers (*a* and *b*) is equivalent to the set of multiples of gcd(*a*, *b*).
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The GCD is said to be the generator of the ideal of *a* and *b*.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] This GCD definition led to the modern abstract algebraic concepts of a principal ideal (an ideal generated by a single element) and a principal ideal domain (a domain in which every ideal is a principal ideal).
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Certain problems can be solved using this result.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] For example, consider two measuring cups of volume *a* and *b*.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] By adding/subtracting *u* multiples of the first cup and *v* multiples of the second cup, any volume *ua* + *vb* can be measured out.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] These volumes are all multiples of *g* = gcd(*a*, *b*).
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The integers *s* and *t* of Bézout's identity can be computed efficiently using the extended Euclidean algorithm.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Using this recursion, Bézout's integers *s* and *t* are given by *s* = *s**N* and *t* = *t**N*, where *N* + 1 is the step on which the algorithm terminates with *r**N*+1 = 0.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The validity of this approach can be shown by induction.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The integers *s* and *t* can also be found using an equivalent matrix method.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] To express *g* as a linear sum of *a* and *b*, both sides of this equation can be multiplied by the inverse of the matrix **M**.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The determinant of **M** equals (−1)*N*+1, since it equals the product of the determinants of the quotient matrices, each of which is negative one.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The matrix method is as efficient as the equivalent recursion, with two multiplications and two additions per step of the Euclidean algorithm.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Bézout's identity is essential to many applications of Euclid's algorithm, such as demonstrating the unique factorization of numbers into prime factors.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] To illustrate this, suppose that a number *L* can be written as a product of two factors *u* and *v*, that is, *L* = *uv*.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Since *w* divides both terms on the right-hand side, it must also divide the left-hand side, *v*.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Specifically, if a prime number divides *L*, then it must divide at least one factor of *L*.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Conversely, if a number *w* is coprime to each of a series of numbers *a*1, *a*2, ..., *a**n*, then *w* is also coprime to their product, *a*1 × *a*2 × ... × *a**n*.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Euclid's lemma suffices to prove that every number has a unique factorization into prime numbers.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Since each prime *p* divides *L* by assumption, it must also divide one of the *q* factors; since each *q* is prime as well, it must be that *p* = *q*.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Iteratively dividing by the *p* factors shows that each *p* has an equal counterpart *q*; the two prime factorizations are identical except for their order.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The unique factorization of numbers into primes has many applications in mathematical proofs, as shown below.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Diophantine equations are equations in which the solutions are restricted to integers; they are named after the 3rd-century Alexandrian mathematician Diophantus.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] where *a*, *b* and *c* are given integers.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Let *g* be the greatest common divisor of *a* and *b*.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Both terms in *ax* + *by* are divisible by *g*; therefore, *c* must also be divisible by *g*, or the equation has no solutions.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] where *s* and *t* can be found by the extended Euclidean algorithm.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] This provides one solution to the Diophantine equation, *x*1 = *s* (*c*/*g*) and *y*1 = *t* (*c*/*g*).
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] In general, a linear Diophantine equation has no solutions, or an infinite number of solutions.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Therefore, the smallest difference between two *x* solutions is *b*/*g*, whereas the smallest difference between two *y* solutions is *a*/*g*.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] By allowing *u* to vary over all possible integers, an infinite family of solutions can be generated from a single solution (*x*1, *y*1).
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] If the solutions are required to be *positive* integers (*x* > 0, *y* > 0), only a finite number of solutions may be possible.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] This restriction on the acceptable solutions allows some systems of Diophantine equations with more unknowns than equations to have a finite number of solutions; this is impossible for a system of linear equations when the solutions can be any real number (see Underdetermined system).
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] A finite field is a set of numbers with four generalized operations.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The operations are called addition, subtraction, multiplication and division and have their usual properties, such as commutativity, associativity and distributivity.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] An example of a finite field is the set of 13 numbers {0, 1, 2, ..., 12} using modular arithmetic.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] In this field, the results of any mathematical operation (addition, subtraction, multiplication, or division) is reduced modulo 13; that is, multiples of 13 are added or subtracted until the result is brought within the range 0–12.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] For example, the result of 5 × 7 = 35 mod 13 = 9.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Such finite fields can be defined for any prime *p*; using more sophisticated definitions, they can also be defined for any power *m* of a prime *p**m*.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Finite fields are often called Galois fields, and are abbreviated as GF(*p*) or GF(*p**m*).
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] In such a field with *m* numbers, every nonzero element *a* has a unique modular multiplicative inverse, *a*−1 such that *aa*−1 = *a*−1*a* ≡ 1 mod *m*.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] This equation can be solved by the Euclidean algorithm, as described above.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Finding multiplicative inverses is an essential step in the RSA algorithm, which is widely used in electronic commerce; specifically, the equation determines the integer used to decrypt the message.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Although the RSA algorithm uses rings rather than fields, the Euclidean algorithm can still be used to find a multiplicative inverse where one exists.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The Euclidean algorithm also has other applications in error-correcting codes; for example, it can be used as an alternative to the Berlekamp–Massey algorithm for decoding BCH and Reed–Solomon codes, which are based on Galois fields.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Euclid's algorithm can also be used to solve multiple linear Diophantine equations.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Such equations arise in the Chinese remainder theorem, which describes a novel method to represent an integer *x*.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The goal is to determine *x* from its *N* remainders *x**i*.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Thus, each *M**i* is the product of all the moduli *except* *m**i*.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Since these numbers *h**i* are the multiplicative inverses of the *M**i*, they may be found using Euclid's algorithm as described in the previous subsection.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The Euclidean algorithm can be used to arrange the set of all positive rational numbers into an infinite binary search tree, called the Stern–Brocot tree.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] A step of the Euclidean algorithm that replaces the first of the two numbers corresponds to a step in the tree from a node to its right child, and a step that replaces the second of the two numbers corresponds to a step in the tree from a node to its left child.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The sequence of steps constructed in this way does not depend on whether *a*/*b* is given in lowest terms, and forms a path from the root to a node containing the number *a*/*b*.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] This fact can be used to prove that each positive rational number appears exactly once in this tree.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The Euclidean algorithm has almost the same relationship to another binary tree on the rational numbers called the Calkin–Wilf tree.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The difference is that the path is reversed: instead of producing a path from the root of the tree to a target, it produces a path from the target to the root.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The Euclidean algorithm has a close relationship with continued fractions.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The last term on the right-hand side always equals the inverse of the left-hand side of the next equation.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The final ratio of remainders *r**k*/*r**k*−1 can always be replaced using the next equation in the series, up to the final equation.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] In the worked example above, the gcd(1071, 462) was calculated, and the quotients *q**k* were 2, 3 and 7, respectively.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Calculating a greatest common divisor is an essential step in several integer factorization algorithms, such as Pollard's rho algorithm, Shor's algorithm, Dixon's factorization method and the Lenstra elliptic curve factorization.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The Euclidean algorithm may be used to find this GCD efficiently.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Continued fraction factorization uses continued fractions, which are determined using Euclid's algorithm.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The computational efficiency of Euclid's algorithm has been studied thoroughly.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] This efficiency can be described by the number of division steps the algorithm requires, multiplied by the computational expense of each step.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The first known analysis of Euclid's algorithm is due to A.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Reynaud in 1811, who showed that the number of division steps on input (*u*, *v*) is bounded by *v*; later he improved this to *v*/2 + 2.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Finck showed that the number of division steps is at most 2 log2 *v* + 1, and hence Euclid's algorithm runs in time polynomial in the size of the input. Émile Léger, in 1837, studied the worst case, which is when the inputs are consecutive Fibonacci numbers.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Finck's analysis was refined by Gabriel Lamé in 1844, who showed that the number of steps required for completion is never more than five times the number *h* of base-10 digits of the smaller number *b*.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] In the uniform cost model (suitable for analyzing the complexity of gcd calculation on numbers that fit into a single machine word), each step of the algorithm takes constant time, and Lamé's analysis implies that the total running time is also *O*(*h*).
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] However, in a model of computation suitable for computation with larger numbers, the computational expense of a single remainder computation in the algorithm can be as large as *O*(*h*2).
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] In this case the total time for all of the steps of the algorithm can be analyzed using a telescoping series, showing that it is also *O*(*h*2).
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Modern algorithmic techniques based on the Schönhage–Strassen algorithm for fast integer multiplication can be used to speed this up, leading to quasilinear algorithms for the GCD.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The number of steps to calculate the GCD of two natural numbers, *a* and *b*, may be denoted by *T*(*a*, *b*).
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] If *g* is the GCD of *a* and *b*, then *a* = *mg* and *b* = *ng* for two coprime numbers *m* and *n*.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] as may be seen by dividing all the steps in the Euclidean algorithm by *g*.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] By the same argument, the number of steps remains the same if *a* and *b* are multiplied by a common factor *w*: *T*(*a*, *b*) = *T*(*wa*, *wb*).
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Therefore, the number of steps *T* may vary dramatically between neighboring pairs of numbers, such as T(*a*, *b*) and T(*a*, *b* + 1), depending on the size of the two GCDs.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] If the Euclidean algorithm requires *N* steps for a pair of natural numbers *a* > *b* > 0, the smallest values of *a* and *b* for which this is true are the Fibonacci numbers *F**N*+2 and *F**N*+1, respectively.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] More precisely, if the Euclidean algorithm requires *N* steps for the pair *a* > *b*, then one has *a* ≥ *F**N*+2 and *b* ≥ *F**N*+1.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] If *N* = 1, *b* divides *a* with no remainder; the smallest natural numbers for which this is true is *b* = 1 and *a* = 2, which are *F*2 and *F*3, respectively.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Now assume that the result holds for all values of *N* up to *M* − 1.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The first step of the *M*-step algorithm is *a* = *q*0*b* + *r*0, and the Euclidean algorithm requires *M* − 1 steps for the pair *b* > *r*0.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] This proof, published by Gabriel Lamé in 1844, represents the beginning of computational complexity theory, and also the first practical application of the Fibonacci numbers.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] This result suffices to show that the number of steps in Euclid's algorithm can never be more than five times the number of its digits (base 10).
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] For if the algorithm requires *N* steps, then *b* is greater than or equal to *F**N*+1 which in turn is greater than or equal to *φ**N*−1, where *φ* is the golden ratio.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Thus, the Euclidean algorithm always needs less than *O*(*h*) divisions, where *h* is the number of digits in the smaller number *b*.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The average number of steps taken by the Euclidean algorithm has been defined in three different ways.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] However, since *T*(*a*, *b*) fluctuates dramatically with the GCD of the two numbers, the averaged function *T*(*a*) is likewise "noisy".
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] There are *φ*(*a*) coprime integers less than *a*, where *φ* is Euler's totient function.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] with the residual error being of order *a*−(1/6)+*ε*, where *ε* is infinitesimal.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] where *γ* is the Euler–Mascheroni constant and *ζ*′ is the derivative of the Riemann zeta function.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The leading coefficient (12/π2) ln 2 was determined by two independent methods.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The computational expense of dividing *h*-bit numbers scales as *O*(*h*(*ℓ* + 1)), where ℓ is the length of the quotient.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] For comparison, Euclid's original subtraction-based algorithm can be much slower.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] A single integer division is equivalent to the quotient *q* number of subtractions.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] If the ratio of *a* and *b* is very large, the quotient is large and many subtractions will be required.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] On the other hand, it has been shown that the quotients are very likely to be small integers.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The probability of a given quotient *q* is approximately ln |*u*/(*u* − 1)| where *u* = (*q* + 1)2.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] For illustration, the probability of a quotient of 1, 2, 3, or 4 is roughly 41.5%, 17.0%, 9.3%, and 5.9%, respectively.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Since the operation of subtraction is faster than division, particularly for large numbers, the subtraction-based Euclid's algorithm is competitive with the division-based version.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] This is exploited in the binary version of Euclid's algorithm.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Combining the estimated number of steps with the estimated computational expense per step shows that the Euclid's algorithm grows quadratically (*h*2) with the average number of digits *h* in the initial two numbers *a* and *b*.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Euclid's algorithm is widely used in practice, especially for small numbers, due to its simplicity.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] For comparison, the efficiency of alternatives to Euclid's algorithm may be determined.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] One inefficient approach to finding the GCD of two natural numbers *a* and *b* is to calculate all their common divisors; the GCD is then the largest common divisor.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The common divisors can be found by dividing both numbers by successive integers from 2 to the smaller number *b*.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The number of steps of this approach grows linearly with *b*, or exponentially in the number of digits.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Another inefficient approach is to find the prime factors of one or both numbers.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] As noted above, the GCD equals the product of the prime factors shared by the two numbers *a* and *b*.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Present methods for prime factorization are also inefficient; many modern cryptography systems even rely on that inefficiency.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The binary GCD algorithm is an efficient alternative that substitutes division with faster operations by exploiting the binary representation used by computers.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] However, this alternative also scales like *O*(*h*²).
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] It is generally faster than the Euclidean algorithm on real computers, even though it scales in the same way.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Additional efficiency can be gleaned by examining only the leading digits of the two numbers *a* and *b*.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The binary algorithm can be extended to other bases (*k*-ary algorithms), with up to fivefold increases in speed.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Lehmer's GCD algorithm uses the same general principle as the binary algorithm to speed up GCD computations in arbitrary bases.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] A recursive approach for very large integers (with more than 25,000 digits) leads to quasilinear integer GCD algorithms, such as those of Schönhage, and Stehlé and Zimmermann.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] These algorithms exploit the 2×2 matrix form of the Euclidean algorithm given above.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] These quasilinear methods generally scale as *O*(*h* log *h*2 log log *h*).
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Although the Euclidean algorithm is used to find the greatest common divisor of two natural numbers (positive integers), it may be generalized to the real numbers, and to other mathematical objects, such as polynomials, quadratic integers and Hurwitz quaternions.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] In the latter cases, the Euclidean algorithm is used to demonstrate the crucial property of unique factorization, i.e., that such numbers can be factored uniquely into irreducible elements, the counterparts of prime numbers.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Unique factorization is essential to many proofs of number theory.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Euclid's algorithm can be applied to real numbers, as described by Euclid in Book 10 of his *Elements*.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The goal of the algorithm is to identify a real number g such that two given real numbers, a and b, are integer multiples of it: *a* = *mg* and *b* = *ng*, where m and n are integers.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] This identification is equivalent to finding an integer relation among the real numbers a and b; that is, it determines integers s and t such that *sa* + *tb* = 0.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] If such an equation is possible, *a* and *b* are called commensurable lengths, otherwise they are incommensurable lengths.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The real-number Euclidean algorithm differs from its integer counterpart in two respects.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] First, the remainders *r**k* are real numbers, although the quotients *q**k* are integers as before.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Second, the algorithm is not guaranteed to end in a finite number N of steps.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] If the algorithm does not stop, the fraction *a*/*b* is an irrational number and can be described by an infinite continued fraction [*q*0; *q*1, *q*2, …].
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Examples of infinite continued fractions are the golden ratio *φ* = [1; 1, 1, ...] and the square root of two, √2 = [1; 2, 2, ...].
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] When applied to two arbitrary real numbers, the algorithm is unlikely to stop, since almost all ratios *a*/*b* of two real numbers are irrational.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] An infinite continued fraction may be truncated at a step *k* [*q*0; *q*1, *q*2, ..., *q**k*] to yield an approximation to *a*/*b* that improves as k is increased.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] where *m*−1 = *n*−2 = 1 and *m*−2 = *n*−1 = 0 are the initial values of the recursion.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Polynomials in a single variable *x* can be added, multiplied and factored into irreducible polynomials, which are the analogs of the prime numbers for integers.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The greatest common divisor polynomial *g*(*x*) of two polynomials *a*(*x*) and *b*(*x*) is defined as the product of their shared irreducible polynomials, which can be identified using the Euclidean algorithm.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The basic procedure is similar to that for integers.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Each quotient polynomial is chosen such that each remainder is either zero or has a degree that is smaller than the degree of its predecessor: deg[*r**k*(*x*)] < deg[*r**k*−1(*x*)].
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Since the degree is a nonnegative integer, and since it decreases with every step, the Euclidean algorithm concludes in a finite number of steps.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The last nonzero remainder is the greatest common divisor of the original two polynomials, *a*(*x*) and *b*(*x*).
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Finally, dividing *r*0(*x*) by *r*1(*x*) yields a zero remainder, indicating that *r*1(*x*) is the greatest common divisor polynomial of *a*(*x*) and *b*(*x*), consistent with their factorization.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Many of the applications described above for integers carry over to polynomials.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The Euclidean algorithm can be used to solve linear Diophantine equations and Chinese remainder problems for polynomials; continued fractions of polynomials can also be defined.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The polynomial Euclidean algorithm has other applications, such as Sturm chains, a method for counting the zeros of a polynomial that lie inside a given real interval.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] This in turn has applications in several areas, such as the Routh–Hurwitz stability criterion in control theory.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Finally, the coefficients of the polynomials need not be drawn from integers, real numbers or even the complex numbers.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] For example, the coefficients may be drawn from a general field, such as the finite fields GF(*p*) described above.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The corresponding conclusions about the Euclidean algorithm and its applications hold even for such polynomials.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The Gaussian integers are complex numbers of the form *α* = *u* + *vi*, where u and v are ordinary integers and i is the square root of negative one.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] By defining an analog of the Euclidean algorithm, Gaussian integers can be shown to be uniquely factorizable, by the argument above.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] This unique factorization is helpful in many applications, such as deriving all Pythagorean triples or proving Fermat's theorem on sums of two squares.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] In general, the Euclidean algorithm is convenient in such applications, but not essential; for example, the theorems can often be proven by other arguments.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The Euclidean algorithm developed for two Gaussian integers α and β is nearly the same as that for ordinary integers, but differs in two respects.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] where every remainder is strictly smaller than its predecessor: |*r**k*| < |*r**k*−1|.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The first difference is that the quotients and remainders are themselves Gaussian integers, and thus are complex numbers.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The quotients *q**k* are generally found by rounding the real and complex parts of the exact ratio (such as the complex number *α*/*β*) to the nearest integers.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The second difference lies in the necessity of defining how one complex remainder can be "smaller" than another.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] To do this, a norm function *f*(*u* + *vi*) = *u*2 + *v*2 is defined, which converts every Gaussian integer *u* + *vi* into an ordinary integer.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] After each step k of the Euclidean algorithm, the norm of the remainder *f*(*r**k*) is smaller than the norm of the preceding remainder, *f*(*r**k*−1).
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Since the norm is a nonnegative integer and decreases with every step, the Euclidean algorithm for Gaussian integers ends in a finite number of steps.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The final nonzero remainder is gcd(*α*, *β*), the Gaussian integer of largest norm that divides both α and β; it is unique up to multiplication by a unit, ±1 or ±*i*.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Many of the other applications of the Euclidean algorithm carry over to Gaussian integers.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] For example, it can be used to solve linear Diophantine equations and Chinese remainder problems for Gaussian integers; continued fractions of Gaussian integers can also be defined.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] A set of elements under two binary operations, denoted as addition and multiplication, is called a Euclidean domain if it forms a commutative ring R and, roughly speaking, if a generalized Euclidean algorithm can be performed on them.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The two operations of such a ring need not be the addition and multiplication of ordinary arithmetic; rather, they can be more general, such as the operations of a mathematical group or monoid.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Nevertheless, these general operations should respect many of the laws governing ordinary arithmetic, such as commutativity, associativity and distributivity.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The generalized Euclidean algorithm requires a *Euclidean function*, i.e., a mapping f from R into the set of nonnegative integers such that, for any two nonzero elements a and b in R, there exist q and r in R such that *a* = *qb* + *r* and *f*(*r*) < *f*(*b*).
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Examples of such mappings are the absolute value for integers, the degree for univariate polynomials, and the norm for Gaussian integers above.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The basic principle is that each step of the algorithm reduces *f* inexorably; hence, if f can be reduced only a finite number of times, the algorithm must stop in a finite number of steps.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] This principle relies on the well-ordering property of the non-negative integers, which asserts that every non-empty set of non-negative integers has a smallest member.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The fundamental theorem of arithmetic applies to any Euclidean domain: Any number from a Euclidean domain can be factored uniquely into irreducible elements.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Any Euclidean domain is a unique factorization domain (UFD), although the converse is not true.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The Euclidean domains and the UFD's are subclasses of the GCD domains, domains in which a greatest common divisor of two numbers always exists.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] In other words, a greatest common divisor may exist (for all pairs of elements in a domain), although it may not be possible to find it using a Euclidean algorithm.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] A Euclidean domain is always a principal ideal domain (PID), an integral domain in which every ideal is a principal ideal.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Again, the converse is not true: not every PID is a Euclidean domain.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The unique factorization of Euclidean domains is useful in many applications.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] For example, the unique factorization of the Gaussian integers is convenient in deriving formulae for all Pythagorean triples and in proving Fermat's theorem on sums of two squares.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Unique factorization was also a key element in an attempted proof of Fermat's Last Theorem published in 1847 by Gabriel Lamé, the same mathematician who analyzed the efficiency of Euclid's algorithm, based on a suggestion of Joseph Liouville.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Lamé's approach required the unique factorization of numbers of the form *x* + *ωy*, where x and y are integers, and *ω* = *e*2*iπ*/*n* is an nth root of 1, that is, *ω**n* = 1.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Although this approach succeeds for some values of n (such as *n* = 3, the Eisenstein integers), in general such numbers do *not* factor uniquely.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] This failure of unique factorization in some cyclotomic fields led Ernst Kummer to the concept of ideal numbers and, later, Richard Dedekind to ideals.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The quadratic integer rings are helpful to illustrate Euclidean domains.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Quadratic integers are generalizations of the Gaussian integers in which the imaginary unit *i* is replaced by a number ω.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Thus, they have the form *u* + *vω*, where u and v are integers and ω has one of two forms, depending on a parameter D.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] If the function f corresponds to a norm function, such as that used to order the Gaussian integers above, then the domain is known as *norm-Euclidean*.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The cases *D* = −1 and *D* = −3 yield the Gaussian integers and Eisenstein integers, respectively.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] If f is allowed to be any Euclidean function, then the list of possible values of D for which the domain is Euclidean is not yet known.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The first example of a Euclidean domain that was not norm-Euclidean (with *D* = 69) was published in 1994.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] In 1973, Weinberger proved that a quadratic integer ring with *D* > 0 is Euclidean if, and only if, it is a principal ideal domain, provided that the generalized Riemann hypothesis holds.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The Euclidean algorithm may be applied to some noncommutative rings such as the set of Hurwitz quaternions.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Let α and β represent two elements from such a ring.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] They have a common right divisor δ if *α* = *ξδ* and *β* = *ηδ* for some choice of ξ and η in the ring.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Similarly, they have a common left divisor if *α* = *dξ* and *β* = *dη* for some choice of ξ and η in the ring.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Since multiplication is not commutative, there are two versions of the Euclidean algorithm, one for right divisors and one for left divisors.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] where *ψ*0 represents the quotient and *ρ*0 the remainder.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Here the quotient and remainder are chosen so that (if nonzero) the remainder has *N*(*ρ*0) < *N*(*β*) for a "Euclidean function" *N* defined analogously to the Euclidean functions of Euclidean domains in the non-commutative case.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] This equation shows that any common right divisor of α and β is likewise a common divisor of the remainder *ρ*0.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] With either choice, the process is repeated as above until the greatest common right or left divisor is identified.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] As in the Euclidean domain, the "size" of the remainder *ρ*0 (formally, its Euclidean function or "norm") must be strictly smaller than β, and there must be only a finite number of possible sizes for *ρ*0, so that the algorithm is guaranteed to terminate.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Many results for the GCD carry over to noncommutative numbers.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] For example, Bézout's identity states that the right gcd(*α*, *β*) can be expressed as a linear combination of α and β.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Bézout's identity can be used to solve Diophantine equations.
[src:number-theory/euclidean-algorithm-p02] For instance, one of the standard proofs of Lagrange's four-square theorem, that every positive integer can be represented as a sum of four squares, is based on quaternion GCDs in this way.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] In number theory, **Euler's totient function** counts the positive integers up to a given integer n that are relatively prime to n .
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] It is written using the Greek letter phi as $\varphi (n)$ or $\phi (n)$ , and may also be called **Euler's phi function**.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] In other words, it is the number of integers k in the range $1\leq k\leq n$ for which the greatest common divisor $\gcd(n,k)$ is equal to 1.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] The integers k of this form are sometimes referred to as totatives of n .
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] For example, the totatives of $n=9$ are the six numbers 1, 2, 4, 5, 7 and 8.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] They are all relatively prime to 9, but the other three numbers in this range, 3, 6, and 9 are not, since $\gcd(9,3)=\gcd(9,6)=3$ and $\gcd(9,9)=9$ .
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] As another example, $\varphi (1)=1$ since for $n=1$ the only integer in the range from 1 to n is 1 itself, and $\gcd(1,1)=1$ .
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] Euler's totient function is a multiplicative function, meaning that if two numbers m and n are relatively prime, then $\varphi (mn)=\varphi (m)\varphi (n)$ .
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] This function gives the order of the multiplicative group of integers modulo n (the group of units of the ring $\mathbb {Z} /n\mathbb {Z}$ ).
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] It is also used for defining the RSA encryption system.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] Leonhard Euler introduced the function in 1763.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] However, he did not at that time choose any specific symbol to denote it.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] In a 1784 publication, Euler studied the function further, choosing the Greek letter $\pi$ to denote it: he wrote $\pi D$ for "the multitude of numbers less than D , and which have no common divisor with it".
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] This definition varies from the current definition for the totient function at $D=1$ but is otherwise the same.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] The now-standard notation $\varphi (A)$ comes from Gauss's 1801 treatise *Disquisitiones Arithmeticae*, although Gauss did not use parentheses around the argument and wrote $\varphi A$ .
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] Thus, it is often called **Euler's phi function** or simply the **phi function**.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] Sylvester coined the term **totient** for this function, so it is also referred to as **Euler's totient function**, the **Euler totient**, or **Euler's totient**.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] Jordan's totient is a generalization of Euler's.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] The **cototient** of n is defined as $n-\varphi (n)$ .
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] It counts the number of positive integers less than or equal to n that have at least one prime factor in common with n .
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] There are several formulae for computing $\varphi (n)$ .
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] where the product is over the distinct prime numbers dividing n.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] The proof of these formulae depends on two important facts.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] This means that if $\gcd(m,n)=1$ , then $\varphi (m)\varphi (n)=\varphi (mn)$ .
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] *Proof outline:* Let $A,B,C$ be the sets of positive integers which are coprime to and less than m, n, mn, respectively, so that $|A|=\varphi (m)$ , etc.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] Then there is a bijection between $A\times B$ and C by the Chinese remainder theorem.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] This gives both versions of Euler's product formula.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] An alternative proof that does not require the multiplicative property instead uses the inclusion-exclusion principle applied to the set $\{1,2,\ldots ,n\}$ , excluding the sets of integers divisible by the prime divisors.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] In words: the distinct prime factors of 20 are 2 and 5; half of the twenty integers from 1 to 20 are divisible by 2, leaving ten; a fifth of those are divisible by 5, leaving eight numbers coprime to 20; these are: 1, 3, 7, 9, 11, 13, 17, 19.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] The totient is the discrete Fourier transform of the gcd, evaluated at 1.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] However, it does involve the calculation of the greatest common divisor of n and every positive integer less than n, which suffices to provide the factorization anyway.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] where the sum is over all positive divisors d of n, can be proven in several ways.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] One proof is to note that *φ*(*d*) is also equal to the number of possible generators of the cyclic group *C**d* ; specifically, if *C**d* = ⟨*g*⟩ with *g**d* = 1, then *g**k* is a generator for every k coprime to d.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] Since every element of *C**n* generates a cyclic subgroup, and each subgroup *C**d* ⊆ *C**n* is generated by precisely *φ*(*d*) elements of *C**n*, the formula follows.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] Equivalently, the formula can be derived by the same argument applied to the multiplicative group of the nth roots of unity and the primitive dth roots of unity.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] The formula can also be derived from elementary arithmetic.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] These twenty fractions are all the positive ⁠*k*/*d*⁠ ≤ 1 whose denominators are the divisors *d* = 1, 2, 4, 5, 10, 20.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] Similarly, there are *φ*(10) fractions with denominator 10, and *φ*(5) fractions with denominator 5, etc.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] Thus the set of twenty fractions is split into subsets of size *φ*(*d*) for each *d* dividing 20.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] where μ is the Möbius function, the multiplicative function defined by $\mu (p)=-1$ and $\mu (p^{k})=0$ for each prime *p* and *k* ≥ 2.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] In the graph at right the top line *y* = *n* − 1 is an upper bound valid for all n other than one, and attained if and only if n is a prime number.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] A simple lower bound is $\varphi (n)\geq {\sqrt {n/2}}$ , which is rather loose: in fact, the lower limit of the graph is proportional to ⁠*n*/log log *n*⁠.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] The special case where n is prime is known as Fermat's little theorem.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] This follows from Lagrange's theorem and the fact that *φ*(*n*) is the order of the multiplicative group of integers modulo n.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] The RSA cryptosystem is based on this theorem: it implies that the inverse of the function *a* ↦ *ae* mod *n*, where e is the (public) encryption exponent, is the function *b* ↦ *bd* mod *n*, where d, the (private) decryption exponent, is the multiplicative inverse of e modulo *φ*(*n*).
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] The difficulty of computing *φ*(*n*) without knowing the factorization of n is thus the difficulty of computing d: this is known as the RSA problem which can be solved by factoring n.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] The owner of the private key knows the factorization, since an RSA private key is constructed by choosing n as the product of two (randomly chosen) large primes p and q.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] Only n is publicly disclosed, and given the difficulty to factor large numbers we have the guarantee that no one else knows the factorization.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] where *d*(*n*) = *σ*0(*n*) is the number of divisors of n.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] The following property, which is unpublished as a specific result but has long been known, has important consequences.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] For instance it rules out uniform distribution of the values of $\varphi (n)$ in the arithmetic progressions modulo q for any integer $q>1$ .
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] This is an elementary consequence of the fact that the sum of the reciprocals of the primes congruent to 1 modulo q diverges, which itself is a corollary of the proof of Dirichlet's theorem on arithmetic progressions.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] where the left-hand side converges for $\Re (s)>2$ .
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] Both of these are proved by elementary series manipulations and the formulae for *φ*(*n*).
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] These two formulae can be proved by using little more than the formulae for *φ*(*n*) and the divisor sum function *σ*(*n*).
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] Proving this does not quite require the prime number theorem.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] The second inequality was shown by Jean-Louis Nicolas.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] due to Arnold Walfisz, its proof exploiting estimates on exponential sums due to I.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] By a combination of van der Corput's and Vinogradov's methods, H.-Q.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] (this is currently the best known estimate of this type).
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] The "Big O" stands for a quantity that is bounded by a constant times the function of n inside the parentheses (which is small compared to *n*2).
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] This result can be used to prove that the probability of two randomly chosen numbers being relatively prime is ⁠6/π2⁠.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] A **totient number** is a value of Euler's totient function: that is, an m for which there is at least one n for which *φ*(*n*) = *m*.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] The *valency* or *multiplicity* of a totient number m is the number of solutions to this equation.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] A *nontotient* is a natural number which is not a totient number.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] Every odd integer exceeding 1 is trivially a nontotient.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] There are also infinitely many even nontotients, and indeed every positive integer has a multiple which is an even nontotient.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] where the error term R is of order at most ⁠*x*/(log *x*)*k*⁠ for any positive k.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] It is known that the multiplicity of m exceeds *m**δ* infinitely often for any *δ* < 0.55655.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] Indeed, each multiplicity that occurs, does so infinitely often.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] However, no number m is known with multiplicity *k* = 1.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] Carmichael's totient function conjecture is the statement that there is no such m.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] A perfect totient number is an integer that is equal to the sum of its iterated totients.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] That is, we apply the totient function to a number *n*, apply it again to the resulting totient, and so on, until the number 1 is reached, and add together the resulting sequence of numbers; if the sum equals *n*, then *n* is a perfect totient number.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] In the last section of the *Disquisitiones* Gauss proves that a regular n-gon can be constructed with straightedge and compass if *φ*(*n*) is a power of 2.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] If n is a power of an odd prime number the formula for the totient says its totient can be a power of two only if n is a first power and *n* − 1 is a power of 2.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] The primes that are one more than a power of 2 are called Fermat primes, and only five are known: 3, 5, 17, 257, and 65537.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] Nobody has been able to prove whether there are any more.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] Thus, a regular n-gon has a straightedge-and-compass construction if *n* is a product of distinct Fermat primes and any power of 2.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] Setting up an RSA system involves choosing large prime numbers p and q, computing *n* = *pq* and *k* = *φ*(*n*), and finding two numbers e and d such that *ed* ≡ 1 (mod *k*).
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] The numbers n and e (the "encryption key") are released to the public, and d (the "decryption key") is kept private.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] A message, represented by an integer m, where 0 < *m* < *n*, is encrypted by computing *S* = *m**e* (mod *n*).
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] It is decrypted by computing *t* = *S**d* (mod *n*).
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] Euler's Theorem can be used to show that if 0 < *t* < *n*, then *t* = *m*.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] The security of an RSA system would be compromised if the number n could be efficiently factored or if *φ*(*n*) could be efficiently computed without factoring n.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] Lehmer asked if there are any composite numbers n such that *φ*(*n*) divides *n* − 1.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] In 1933 he proved that if any such n exists, it must be odd, square-free, and divisible by at least seven primes (i.e.
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] This states that there is no number n with the property that for all other numbers m , $m\neq n$ , $\varphi (m)\neq \varphi (n)$ .
[src:number-theory/euler-s-totient-function] If there is a single counterexample to this conjecture, there must be infinitely many counterexamples, and the smallest one has at least ten billion digits in base 10.
[src:number-theory/fermat-s-little-theorem] In number theory, **Fermat's little theorem** states that if p is a prime number, then for any integer a, the number *a**p* − *a* is an integer multiple of p.
[src:number-theory/fermat-s-little-theorem] Fermat's little theorem is the basis for the Fermat primality test and is one of the fundamental results of elementary number theory.
[src:number-theory/fermat-s-little-theorem] The theorem is named after Pierre de Fermat, who stated it in 1640.
[src:number-theory/fermat-s-little-theorem] It is called the "little theorem" to distinguish it from Fermat's Last Theorem.
[src:number-theory/fermat-s-little-theorem] Pierre de Fermat first stated the theorem in a letter dated October 18, 1640, to his friend and confidant Frénicle de Bessy.
[src:number-theory/fermat-s-little-theorem] Euler provided the first published proof in 1736, in a paper titled "Theorematum Quorundam ad Numeros Primos Spectantium Demonstratio" (in English: "Demonstration of Certain Theorems Concerning Prime Numbers") in the *Proceedings* of the St.
[src:number-theory/fermat-s-little-theorem] Petersburg Academy, but Leibniz had given virtually the same proof in an unpublished manuscript from sometime before 1683.
[src:number-theory/fermat-s-little-theorem] Albert's *Modern Higher Algebra* (1937), which refers to "the so-called 'little' Fermat theorem" on page 206.
[src:number-theory/fermat-s-little-theorem] Some mathematicians independently made the related hypothesis (sometimes incorrectly called the Chinese hypothesis) that 2*p* ≡ 2 (mod *p*) if and only if p is prime.
[src:number-theory/fermat-s-little-theorem] Indeed, the "if" part is true, and it is a special case of Fermat's little theorem.
[src:number-theory/fermat-s-little-theorem] However, the "only if" part is false: For example, 2341 ≡ 2 (mod 341), but 341 = 11 × 31 is a pseudoprime to base 2.
[src:number-theory/fermat-s-little-theorem] Several proofs of Fermat's little theorem are known.
[src:number-theory/fermat-s-little-theorem] It is frequently proved as a corollary of Euler's theorem.
[src:number-theory/fermat-s-little-theorem] where *φ*(*n*) denotes Euler's totient function (which counts the integers from 1 to n that are coprime to n).
[src:number-theory/fermat-s-little-theorem] Fermat's little theorem is indeed a special case, because if n is a prime number, then *φ*(*n*) = *n* − 1.
[src:number-theory/fermat-s-little-theorem] A corollary of Euler's theorem is: For every positive integer n, if the integer a is coprime with n, then $x\equiv y{\pmod {\varphi (n)}}\quad {\text{implies}}\quad a^{x}\equiv a^{y}{\pmod {n}},$ for any integers x and y.
[src:number-theory/fermat-s-little-theorem] If n is prime, this is also a corollary of Fermat's little theorem.
[src:number-theory/fermat-s-little-theorem] This is widely used in modular arithmetic, because this allows reducing modular exponentiation with large exponents to exponents smaller than n.
[src:number-theory/fermat-s-little-theorem] Euler's theorem is used with n not prime in public-key cryptography, specifically in the RSA cryptosystem, typically in the following way: if $y=x^{e}{\pmod {n}},$ retrieving x from the values of y, e and n is easy if one knows *φ*(*n*).
[src:number-theory/fermat-s-little-theorem] On the other hand, if *n* = *pq* is the product of two distinct prime numbers, then *φ*(*n*) = (*p* − 1)(*q* − 1).
[src:number-theory/fermat-s-little-theorem] In this case, finding f from n and e is as difficult as computing *φ*(*n*) (this has not been proven, but no algorithm is known for computing f without knowing *φ*(*n*)).
[src:number-theory/fermat-s-little-theorem] Knowing only n, the computation of *φ*(*n*) has essentially the same difficulty as the factorization of n, since *φ*(*n*) = (*p* − 1)(*q* − 1), and conversely, the factors p and q are the (integer) solutions of the equation *x*2 − (*n* − *φ*(*n*) + 1) *x* + *n* = 0.
[src:number-theory/fermat-s-little-theorem] The basic idea of RSA cryptosystem is thus: If a message x is encrypted as *y* = *xe* (mod *n*), using public values of n and e, then, with the current knowledge, it cannot be decrypted without finding the (secret) factors p and q of n.
[src:number-theory/fermat-s-little-theorem] Fermat's little theorem is also related to the Carmichael function and Carmichael's theorem, as well as to Lagrange's theorem in group theory.
[src:number-theory/fermat-s-little-theorem] The converse of Fermat's little theorem fails for Carmichael numbers.
[src:number-theory/fermat-s-little-theorem] If there exists an integer a such that $a^{p-1}\equiv 1{\pmod {p}}$ and for all primes q dividing *p* − 1 one has $a^{(p-1)/q}\not \equiv 1{\pmod {p}},$ then p is prime.
[src:number-theory/fermat-s-little-theorem] This theorem forms the basis for the Lucas primality test, an important primality test, and Pratt's primality certificate.
[src:number-theory/fermat-s-little-theorem] If a and p are coprime numbers such that *a**p*−1 − 1 is divisible by p, then p need not be prime.
[src:number-theory/fermat-s-little-theorem] If it is not, then p is called a *(Fermat) pseudoprime* to base a.
[src:number-theory/fermat-s-little-theorem] The first pseudoprime to base 2 was found in 1820 by Pierre Frédéric Sarrus: 341 = 11 × 31.
[src:number-theory/fermat-s-little-theorem] A number p that is a Fermat pseudoprime to base a for every number a coprime to p is called a Carmichael number.
[src:number-theory/fermat-s-little-theorem] Alternately, any number p satisfying the equality $\gcd \left(p,\sum _{a=1}^{p-1}a^{p-1}\right)=1$ is either a prime or a Carmichael number.
[src:number-theory/fermat-s-little-theorem] This result may be deduced from Fermat's little theorem by the fact that, if p is an odd prime, then the integers modulo p form a finite field, in which 1 modulo p has exactly two square roots, 1 and −1 modulo p.
[src:number-theory/fermat-s-little-theorem] Note that *a**d* ≡ 1 (mod *p*) holds trivially for *a* ≡ 1 (mod *p*), because the congruence relation is compatible with exponentiation.
[src:number-theory/fermat-s-little-theorem] And *a**d* = *a*20*d* ≡ −1 (mod *p*) holds trivially for *a* ≡ −1 (mod *p*) since d is odd, for the same reason.
[src:number-theory/fermat-s-little-theorem] That is why one usually chooses a random a in the interval 1 < *a* < *p* − 1.
[src:number-theory/fermat-s-little-theorem] If *b* ≠ 1 and −1 has not been obtained by squaring, then p is a *composite* and a is a witness for the compositeness of p.
[src:number-theory/fermat-s-little-theorem] Otherwise, p is a *strong probable prime to base a*; that is, it may be prime or not.
[src:number-theory/fermat-s-little-theorem] If p is composite, the probability that the test declares it a strong probable prime anyway is at most 1⁄4, in which case p is a *strong pseudoprime*, and a is a *strong liar*.
[src:number-theory/fermat-s-little-theorem] Therefore after k non-conclusive random tests, the probability that p is composite is at most 4−*k*, and may thus be made as low as desired by increasing k.
[src:number-theory/fermat-s-little-theorem] In summary, the test either proves that a number is composite or asserts that it is prime with a probability of error that may be chosen as low as desired.
[src:number-theory/fermat-s-little-theorem] The test is very simple to implement and computationally more efficient than all known deterministic tests.
[src:number-theory/fermat-s-little-theorem] Therefore, it is generally used before starting a proof of primality.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] In mathematics, the **greatest common divisor** (**GCD**), also known as **greatest common factor (GCF)**, of two or more integers, which are not all zero, is the largest positive integer that divides each of the integers.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] For two integers *x*, *y*, the greatest common divisor of *x* and *y* is denoted $\gcd(x,y)$ .
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] For example, the GCD of 8 and 12 is 4, that is, gcd(8, 12) = 4.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] In the name "greatest common divisor", the adjective "greatest" may be replaced by "highest", and the word "divisor" may be replaced by "factor", so that other names include **highest common factor (HCF)**, etc.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] Historically, other names for the same concept have included **greatest common measure**.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] This notion can be extended to polynomials (see *Polynomial greatest common divisor*) and other commutative rings (see *§ In commutative rings* below).
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] The *greatest common divisor* (GCD) of integers a and b, at least one of which is nonzero, is the greatest positive integer d such that d is a divisor of both a and b; that is, there are integers e and f such that *a* = *de* and *b* = *df*, and d is the largest such integer.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] The GCD of a and b is generally denoted gcd(*a*, *b*).
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] When one of *a* and *b* is zero, the GCD is the absolute value of the nonzero integer: gcd(*a*, 0) = gcd(0, *a*) = |*a*|.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] This case is important as the terminating step of the Euclidean algorithm.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] The above definition is unsuitable for defining gcd(0, 0), since there is no greatest integer *n* such that 0 × *n* = 0.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] However, zero is its own greatest divisor if *greatest* is understood in the context of the divisibility relation, so gcd(0, 0) is commonly defined as 0.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] This preserves the usual identities for GCD, and in particular Bézout's identity, namely that gcd(*a*, *b*) generates the same ideal as {*a*, *b*}.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] This convention is followed by many computer algebra systems.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] Nonetheless, some authors leave gcd(0, 0) undefined.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] The GCD of a and b is their greatest positive common divisor in the preorder relation of divisibility.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] This means that the common divisors of a and b are exactly the divisors of their GCD.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] This is commonly proved by using either Euclid's lemma, the fundamental theorem of arithmetic, or the Euclidean algorithm.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] This is the meaning of "greatest" that is used for the generalizations of the concept of GCD.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] Computing all divisors of the two numbers in this way is usually not efficient, especially for large numbers that have many divisors.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] Much more efficient methods are described in *§ Calculation*.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] Two numbers are called relatively prime, or coprime, if their greatest common divisor equals 1.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] For example, a 24-by-60 rectangular area can be divided into a grid of: 1-by-1 squares, 2-by-2 squares, 3-by-3 squares, 4-by-4 squares, 6-by-6 squares or 12-by-12 squares.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] Therefore, 12 is the greatest common divisor of 24 and 60.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] A 24-by-60 rectangular area can thus be divided into a grid of 12-by-12 squares, with two squares along one edge (24/12 = 2) and five squares along the other (60/12 = 5).
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] The greatest common divisor is useful for reducing fractions to the lowest terms.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] Greatest common divisors can be computed by determining the prime factorizations of the two numbers and comparing factors.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] In practice, this method is only feasible for small numbers, as computing prime factorizations takes too long.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] The method introduced by Euclid for computing greatest common divisors is based on the fact that, given two positive integers a and b such that *a* > *b*, the common divisors of a and b are the same as the common divisors of *a* – *b* and b.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] So, Euclid's method for computing the greatest common divisor of two positive integers consists of replacing the larger number with the difference of the numbers, and repeating this until the two numbers are equal: that is their greatest common divisor.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] This method can be very slow if one number is much larger than the other.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] So, the variant that follows is generally preferred.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] A more efficient method is the *Euclidean algorithm*, a variant in which the difference of the two numbers a and b is replaced by the *remainder* of the Euclidean division (also called *division with remainder*) of a by b.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] Denoting this remainder as *a* mod *b*, the algorithm replaces (*a*, *b*) with (*b*, *a* mod *b*) repeatedly until the pair is (*d*, 0), where d is the greatest common divisor.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] The binary GCD algorithm is a variant of Euclid's algorithm that is specially adapted to the binary representation of the numbers, which is used in most computers.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] The binary GCD algorithm differs from Euclid's algorithm essentially by dividing by two every even number that is encountered during the computation.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] Its efficiency results from the fact that, in binary representation, testing parity consists of testing the right-most digit, and dividing by two consists of removing the right-most digit.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] The method is as follows, starting with *a* and *b* that are the two positive integers whose GCD is sought.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] If *a* is even, then divide it by two until it becomes odd.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] If *b* is even, then divide it by two until it becomes odd.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] Step 1 determines d as the highest power of 2 that divides *a* and *b*, and thus their greatest common divisor.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] None of the steps changes the set of the odd common divisors of *a* and *b*.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] This shows that when the algorithm stops, the result is correct.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] The algorithm stops eventually, since each steps divides at least one of the operands by at least 2.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] Moreover, the number of divisions by 2 and thus the number of subtractions is at most the total number of digits.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] The binary GCD algorithm is particularly easy to implement and particularly efficient on binary computers.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] The square in this complexity comes from the fact that division by 2 and subtraction take a time that is proportional to the number of bits of the input.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] The computational complexity is usually given in terms of the length *n* of the input.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] Lehmer's algorithm is based on the observation that the initial quotients produced by Euclid's algorithm can be determined based on only the first few digits; this is useful for numbers that are larger than a computer word.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] In essence, one extracts initial digits, typically forming one or two computer words, and runs Euclid's algorithms on these smaller numbers, as long as it is guaranteed that the quotients are the same with those that would be obtained with the original numbers.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] The quotients are collected into a small 2-by-2 transformation matrix (a matrix of single-word integers) to reduce the original numbers.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] This process is repeated until numbers are small enough that the binary algorithm (see below) is more efficient.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] This algorithm improves speed, because it reduces the number of operations on very large numbers, and can use hardware arithmetic for most operations.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] In fact, most of the quotients are very small, so a fair number of steps of the Euclidean algorithm can be collected in a 2-by-2 matrix of single-word integers.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] When Lehmer's algorithm encounters a quotient that is too large, it must fall back to one iteration of Euclidean algorithm, with a Euclidean division of large numbers.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] but more commonly the LCM is computed from the GCD.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] which generalizes to *a* and *b* rational numbers or commensurable real numbers.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] which is a function that can be evaluated for complex *b*.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] is an entire function in the variable *b* for all positive integers *a* where *c**d*(*k*) is Ramanujan's sum.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] The computational complexity of the computation of greatest common divisors has been widely studied.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] If one uses the Euclidean algorithm and the elementary algorithms for multiplication and division, the computation of the greatest common divisor of two integers of at most n bits is *O*(*n*2).
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] This means that the computation of greatest common divisor has, up to a constant factor, the same complexity as the multiplication.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] However, if a fast multiplication algorithm is used, one may modify the Euclidean algorithm for improving the complexity, but the computation of a greatest common divisor becomes slower than the multiplication.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] More precisely, if the multiplication of two integers of *n* bits takes a time of *T*(*n*), then the fastest known algorithm for greatest common divisor has a complexity *O*(*T*(*n*) log *n*).
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] This implies that the fastest known algorithm has a complexity of *O*(*n* (log *n*)2).
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] Previous complexities are valid for the usual models of computation, specifically multitape Turing machines and random-access machines.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] The computation of the greatest common divisors belongs thus to the class of problems solvable in quasilinear time.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] *A fortiori*, the corresponding decision problem belongs to the class P of problems solvable in polynomial time.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] The GCD problem is not known to be in NC, and so there is no known way to parallelize it efficiently; nor is it known to be P-complete, which would imply that it is unlikely to be possible to efficiently parallelize GCD computation.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] Shallcross et al. showed that a related problem (EUGCD, determining the remainder sequence arising during the Euclidean algorithm) is NC-equivalent to the problem of integer linear programming with two variables; if either problem is in **NC** or is **P-complete**, the other is as well.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] Since **NC** contains NL, it is also unknown whether a space-efficient algorithm for computing the GCD exists, even for nondeterministic Turing machines.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] Although the problem is not known to be in **NC**, parallel algorithms asymptotically faster than the Euclidean algorithm exist; the fastest known deterministic algorithm is by Chor and Goldreich, which (in the CRCW-PRAM model) can solve the problem in *O*(*n*/log *n*) time with *n*1+*ε* processors.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] Randomized algorithms can solve the problem in *O*((log *n*)2) time on $O\left(e^{\sqrt {n\log n}}\right)$ processors (this is superpolynomial).
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] This formula is often used to compute least common multiples: one first computes the GCD with Euclid's algorithm and then divides the product of the given numbers by their GCD.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] Nymann showed that *k* integers, chosen independently and uniformly from {1, ..., *n*}, are coprime with probability 1/*ζ*(*k*) as *n* goes to infinity, where *ζ* refers to the Riemann zeta function.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] (See coprime for a derivation.) This result was extended in 1987 to show that the probability that *k* random integers have greatest common divisor *d* is *d*−*k*/ζ(*k*).
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] Using this information, the expected value of the greatest common divisor function can be seen (informally) to not exist when *k* = 2.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] This last summation is the harmonic series, which diverges.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] For *k* = 3, this is approximately equal to 1.3684.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] The notion of greatest common divisor can more generally be defined for elements of an arbitrary commutative ring, although in general there need not exist one for every pair of elements.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] With this definition, two elements a and b may very well have several greatest common divisors, or none at all.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] If R is an integral domain, then any two GCDs of a and b must be associate elements, since by definition either one must divide the other.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] Indeed, if a GCD exists, any one of its associates is a GCD as well.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] Existence of a GCD is not assured in arbitrary integral domains.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] However, if R is a unique factorization domain or any other GCD domain, then any two elements have a GCD.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] The elements 2 and $1+{\sqrt {-3}}$ are two maximal common divisors (that is, any common divisor which is a multiple of 2 is associated to 2, the same holds for $1+{\sqrt {-3}}$ , but they are not associated, so there is no greatest common divisor of a and *b*.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] Corresponding to the Bézout property we may, in any commutative ring, consider the collection of elements of the form *pa* + *qb*, where p and q range over the ring.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] This is the ideal generated by a and b, and is denoted simply (*a*, *b*).
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] In a ring all of whose ideals are principal (a principal ideal domain or PID), this ideal will be identical with the set of multiples of some ring element *d*; then this d is a greatest common divisor of a and *b*.
[src:number-theory/greatest-common-divisor] But the ideal (*a*, *b*) can be useful even when there is no greatest common divisor of a and *b*.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] In mathematics, **modular arithmetic** is a system of arithmetic operations for integers, differing from the usual ones in that numbers "wrap around" when reaching or exceeding a certain value, called the **modulus**.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] The modern approach to number theory using modular arithmetic was developed by Carl Friedrich Gauss in his book *Disquisitiones Arithmeticae*, published in 1801.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] A familiar setting exhibiting modular arithmetic is the hour hand on a 12-hour clock.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] If the hour hand points to 7 now, then 8 hours later it will point to 3.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] Ordinary addition would result in 7 + 8 = 15, but 15 reads as 3 on the clock face.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] This is because the hour hand makes one rotation every 12 hours and the hour number starts over when the hour hand passes 12.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] We say that 15 is *congruent* to 3 modulo 12, and we write 15 ≡ 3 (mod 12), so 7 + 8 ≡ 3 (mod 12).
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] Similarly, if one waits 8 hours and then 8 more hours (thus 16 hours in total), the clock will show the same time change as if one waited 4 hours.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] This is reflected by the identity 2 × 8 ≡ 4 (mod 12).
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] After a wait of exactly 12 hours, the hour hand will be right where it started, so 12 acts as 0; one writes 12 ≡ 0 (mod 12).
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] Congruence modulo m is a congruence relation, meaning that it is an equivalence relation compatible with addition, subtraction, and multiplication.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] The parentheses mean that (mod *m*) applies to the entire equation, not just to the right-hand side (here, b).
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] The congruence relation *a* ≡ *b* (mod *m*) may be rewritten as $\exists k\in \mathbb {Z} \quad a=km+b,$ explicitly showing its relationship with Euclidean division.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] However, the *b* here need not be the remainder in the division of *a* by *m*.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] Rather, *a* ≡ *b* (mod *m*) asserts that *a* and *b* have the same remainder when divided by *m*.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] where 0 ≤ *r* < *m* is the common remainder.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] We recover the previous relation (*a* − *b* = *k m*) by subtracting these two expressions and setting *k* = *p* − *q*.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] Because the congruence modulo m is defined by the divisibility by m and because −1 is a unit in the ring of integers, a number is divisible by −*m* exactly if it is divisible by m.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] This means that every non-zero integer m may be taken as a modulus.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] because the difference is 38 − 14 = 24 = 2 × 12, a multiple of 12.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] Equivalently, 38 and 14 have the same remainder 2 when divided by 12.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] The definition of congruence also applies to negative values.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] If *a* ≡ *b* (mod *m*), then it is generally false that *ka* ≡ *kb* (mod *m*).
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] The last rule can be used to move modular arithmetic into division.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] The multiplicative inverse *x* ≡ *a*−1 (mod *m*) may be efficiently computed by solving Bézout's equation *a x* + *m y* = 1 for *x*, *y*, by using the Extended Euclidean algorithm.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] In particular, if *p* is a prime number, then *a* is coprime with *p* for every *a* such that 0 < *a* < *p*; thus a multiplicative inverse exists for all *a* that is not congruent to zero modulo *p*.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] The congruence relation is an equivalence relation.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] The equivalence class modulo m of an integer *a* is the set of all integers of the form *a* + *k m*, where k is any integer.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] It is called the **congruence class** or **residue class** of *a* modulo *m*, and may be denoted (*a* mod *m*), or as *a* or [*a*] when the modulus *m* is known from the context.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] Each residue class modulo *m* contains exactly one integer in the range $0,...,|m|-1$ .
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] Thus, these $|m|$ integers are representatives of their respective residue classes.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] It is generally easier to work with integers than sets of integers; that is, the representatives most often considered, rather than their residue classes.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] Consequently, (*a* mod *m*) denotes generally the unique integer r such that 0 ≤ *r* < *m* and *r* ≡ *a* (mod *m*); it is called the **residue** of *a* modulo *m*.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] In particular, (*a* mod *m*) = (*b* mod *m*) is equivalent to *a* ≡ *b* (mod *m*), and this explains why "=" is often used instead of "≡" in this context.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] Each residue class modulo *m* may be represented by any one of its members, although we usually represent each residue class by the smallest nonnegative integer which belongs to that class (since this is the proper remainder which results from division).
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] Any two members of different residue classes modulo *m* are incongruent modulo *m*.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] Furthermore, every integer belongs to one and only one residue class modulo *m*.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] The set of integers {0, 1, 2, ..., *m* − 1} is called the **least residue system modulo *m***.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] Any set of *m* integers, no two of which are congruent modulo *m*, is called a **complete residue system modulo *m***.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] The least residue system is a complete residue system, and a complete residue system is simply a set containing precisely one representative of each residue class modulo *m*.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] For example, the least residue system modulo 4 is {0, 1, 2, 3}.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] Given the Euler's totient function *φ*(*m*), any set of *φ*(*m*) integers that are relatively prime to *m* and mutually incongruent under modulus *m* is called a **reduced residue system modulo *m***.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] The set {5, 15} from above, for example, is an instance of a reduced residue system modulo 4.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] Covering systems represent yet another type of residue system that may contain residues with varying moduli.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] In the context of this paragraph, the modulus *m* is almost always taken as positive.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] The set of all congruence classes modulo *m* is a ring called the **ring of integers modulo *m***, and is denoted ${\textstyle \mathbb {Z} /m\mathbb {Z} }$ , $\mathbb {Z} /(m)$ , $\mathbb {Z} /m$ , or $\mathbb {Z} _{m}$ .
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] The ring $\mathbb {Z} /m\mathbb {Z}$ is fundamental to various branches of mathematics (see *§ Applications* below).
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] When *m* = 1, $\mathbb {Z} /m\mathbb {Z}$ is the zero ring; when *m* = 0, $\mathbb {Z} /m\mathbb {Z}$ is not an empty set; rather, it is isomorphic to $\mathbb {Z}$ , since *a*0 = {*a*}.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] The properties given before imply that, with these operations, $\mathbb {Z} /m\mathbb {Z}$ is a commutative ring.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] as in the arithmetic for the 24-hour clock.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] Under addition, $\mathbb {Z} /m\mathbb {Z}$ is a cyclic group.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] All finite cyclic groups are isomorphic with $\mathbb {Z} /m\mathbb {Z}$ for some m.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] The ring of integers modulo *m* is a field; that is, every nonzero element has a multiplicative inverse, if and only if *m* is prime.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] If *m* = *p**k* is a prime power with *k* > 1, there exists a unique (up to isomorphism) finite field $\mathrm {GF} (m)=\mathbb {F} _{m}$ with *m* elements, which is *not* isomorphic to $\mathbb {Z} /m\mathbb {Z}$ , which fails to be a field because it has zero-divisors.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] If *m* > 1, $(\mathbb {Z} /m\mathbb {Z} )^{\times }$ denotes the multiplicative group of the integers modulo *m* that are invertible.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] It consists of the congruence classes *a**m*, where *a* is coprime to *m*; these are precisely the classes possessing a multiplicative inverse.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] They form an abelian group under multiplication; its order is *φ*(*m*), where φ is Euler's totient function.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] In pure mathematics, modular arithmetic is one of the foundations of number theory, touching on almost every aspect of its study, and it is also used extensively in group theory, ring theory, knot theory, and abstract algebra.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] In applied mathematics, it is used in computer algebra, cryptography, computer science, chemistry and the visual and musical arts.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] A very practical application is to calculate checksums within serial number identifiers.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] For example, International Standard Book Number (ISBN) uses modulo 11 (for 10-digit ISBN) or modulo 10 (for 13-digit ISBN) arithmetic for error detection.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] Likewise, International Bank Account Numbers (IBANs) use modulo 97 arithmetic to spot user input errors in bank account numbers.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] RSA and Diffie–Hellman use modular exponentiation.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] In computer algebra, modular arithmetic is commonly used to limit the size of integer coefficients in intermediate calculations and data.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] It is used in polynomial factorization, a problem for which all known efficient algorithms use modular arithmetic.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] It is used by the most efficient implementations of polynomial greatest common divisor, exact linear algebra and Gröbner basis algorithms over the integers and the rational numbers.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] In computer science, modular arithmetic is often applied in bitwise operations and other operations involving fixed-width, cyclic data structures.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] The modulo operation, as implemented in many programming languages and calculators, is an application of modular arithmetic that is often used in this context.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] The logical operator XOR sums 2 bits, modulo 2.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] The use of long division to turn a fraction into a repeating decimal in any base *b* is equivalent to modular multiplication of *b* modulo the denominator.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] In music, arithmetic modulo 12 is used in the consideration of the system of twelve-tone equal temperament, where octave and enharmonic equivalency occurs (that is, pitches in a 1:2 or 2:1 ratio are equivalent, and C-sharp is considered the same as D-flat).
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] The method of casting out nines offers a quick check of decimal arithmetic computations performed by hand.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] It is based on modular arithmetic modulo 9, and specifically on the crucial property that 10 ≡ 1 (mod 9).
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] Arithmetic modulo 7 is used in algorithms that determine the day of the week for a given date.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] In particular, Zeller's congruence and the Doomsday algorithm make heavy use of modulo-7 arithmetic.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] More generally, modular arithmetic also has application in disciplines such as politics (for example, apportionment), economics (for example, game theory) and other areas of the social sciences, where proportional division and allocation of resources plays a central part of the analysis.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] Since modular arithmetic has such a wide range of applications, it is important to know how hard it is to solve a system of congruences.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] A linear system of congruences can be solved in polynomial time with a form of Gaussian elimination, for details see linear congruence theorem.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] Algorithms, such as Montgomery reduction, also exist to allow simple arithmetic operations, such as multiplication and exponentiation modulo *m*, to be performed efficiently on large numbers.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] Some operations, like finding a discrete logarithm or a quadratic congruence appear to be as hard as integer factorization and thus are a starting point for cryptographic algorithms and encryption.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] These problems might be NP-intermediate.
[src:number-theory/modular-arithmetic] Solving a system of non-linear modular arithmetic equations is NP-complete.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Integers can be considered either in themselves or as solutions to equations (Diophantine geometry).
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Questions in number theory can often be understood through the study of analytical objects, such as the Riemann zeta function, that encode properties of the integers, primes or other number-theoretic objects in some fashion (analytic number theory).
[src:number-theory/number-theory] One may also study real numbers in relation to rational numbers, as for instance how irrational numbers can be approximated by fractions (Diophantine approximation).
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Number theory is one of the oldest branches of mathematics alongside geometry.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] One quirk of number theory is that it deals with statements that are simple to understand but are very difficult to solve.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Examples of this are Fermat's Last Theorem, which was proved 358 years after the original formulation, and Goldbach's conjecture, which remains unsolved since the 18th century.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Number theory is the branch of mathematics that studies integers and their properties and relations.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] The integers comprise a set that extends the set of natural numbers $\{1,2,3,\dots \}$ to include number 0 and the negation of natural numbers $\{-1,-2,-3,\dots \}$ .
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Number theorists study prime numbers as well as the properties of mathematical objects constructed from integers (for example, rational numbers), or defined as generalizations of the integers (for example, algebraic integers).
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Number theory is closely related to arithmetic and some authors use the terms as synonyms.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] However, the word "arithmetic" is used today to mean the study of numerical operations and extends to the real numbers.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] In a more specific sense, number theory is restricted to the study of integers and focuses on their properties and relationships.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Traditionally, it is known as higher arithmetic.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] By the early twentieth century, the term *number theory* had been widely adopted.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] The term number means whole numbers, which refers to either the natural numbers or the integers.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Elementary number theory studies aspects of integers that can be investigated using elementary methods such as elementary proofs.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Analytic number theory, by contrast, relies on complex numbers and techniques from analysis and calculus.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Algebraic number theory employs algebraic structures such as fields and rings to analyze the properties of and relations between numbers.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Geometric number theory uses concepts from geometry to study numbers.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Further branches of number theory are probabilistic number theory, combinatorial number theory, computational number theory, and applied number theory, which examines the application of number theory to science and technology.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] In recorded history, knowledge of numbers existed in the ancient civilisations of Mesopotamia, Egypt, China, and India.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] The earliest historical find of an arithmetical nature is the Plimpton 322, dated c.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] It is a broken clay tablet that contains a list of Pythagorean triples, that is, integers $(a,b,c)$ such that $a^{2}+b^{2}=c^{2}$ .
[src:number-theory/number-theory] The triples are too numerous and too large to have been obtained by brute force.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] The table's layout suggests that it was constructed by means of what amounts, in modern language, to the identity $\left({\frac {1}{2}}\left(x-{\frac {1}{x}}\right)\right)^{2}+1=\left({\frac {1}{2}}\left(x+{\frac {1}{x}}\right)\right)^{2},$ which is implicit in routine Old Babylonian exercises.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] It has been suggested instead that the table was a source of numerical examples for school problems.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Plimpton 322 tablet is the only surviving evidence of what today would be called number theory within Babylonian mathematics, though a kind of Babylonian algebra was much more developed.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Although other civilizations probably influenced Greek mathematics at the beginning, all evidence of such borrowings appear relatively late, and it is likely that Greek *arithmētikḗ*, the theoretical or philosophical study of numbers, is an indigenous tradition.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Ancient Greek mathematicians conventionally separated numbers (mostly positive integers but occasionally rationals) from magnitudes or lengths, with only the former being the subject of arithmetic.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] A keen interest in divisibility is found in early Greek arithmetic.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Pythagoreans often attributed mystical qualities to perfect and amicable numbers, and dedicated time to the study polygonal or figurate numbers.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Later, Euclid devoted part of his *Elements* to topics that belong to elementary number theory, including prime numbers and divisibility.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] He gave the Euclidean algorithm for computing the greatest common divisor of two numbers and a proof implying the infinitude of primes.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Building on the works of the earlier Pythagoreans, Nicomachus of Gerasa wrote an *Introduction to Arithmetic* that was to be influential in later centuries, while Theon of Smyrna's *Mathematics Useful For Understanding Plato* discusses the idea of congruences.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] The most important late antique author was arguably Diophantus of Alexandria, who probably lived in the 3rd century AD.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] He wrote the *Arithmetica*, a collection of worked-out problems where the task is invariably to find rational solutions to a system of polynomial equations, usually of the form $f(x,y)=z^{2}$ or $f(x,y,z)=w^{2}$ .
[src:number-theory/number-theory] In modern parlance, Diophantine equations are polynomial equations to which rational or integer solutions are sought.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] After the fall of Rome, development shifted to Asia, albeit intermittently.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] The Chinese remainder theorem appears as an exercise in *Sunzi Suanjing* (between the third and fifth centuries).
[src:number-theory/number-theory] The result was later generalized with a complete solution called *Da-yan-shu* (大衍術) in Qin Jiushao's 1247 *Mathematical Treatise in Nine Sections.* There is also some numerical mysticism in Chinese mathematics, but, unlike that of the Pythagoreans, it seems to have led nowhere.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Brahmagupta (628 AD) started the systematic study of indefinite quadratic equations—in particular, the Pell equation.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] A general procedure for solving Pell's equation was probably found by Jayadeva; the earliest surviving exposition appears in Bhāskara II's Bīja-gaṇita (twelfth century).
[src:number-theory/number-theory] In the early ninth century, the caliph al-Ma'mun ordered translations of many Greek mathematical works and at least one Sanskrit work.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Diophantus's main work, the *Arithmetica*, was translated into Arabic by Qusta ibn Luqa (820–912).
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Part of the treatise *al-Fakhri* (by al-Karajī, 953 – c.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] According to Rashed Roshdi, Al-Karajī's contemporary Ibn al-Haytham knew what would later be called Wilson's theorem.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Other than a treatise on squares in arithmetic progression by Fibonacci no number theory to speak of was done in western Europe during the Middle Ages.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Matters started to change in Europe in the late Renaissance, thanks to a renewed study of the works of Greek antiquity.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] A catalyst was the textual emendation and translation into Latin of Diophantus' *Arithmetica*.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] French mathematician Pierre de Fermat (1607–1665) never published his writings but communicated through correspondence and wrote in marginal notes instead.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] His contributions to number theory brought renewed interest in the field in Europe.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] He conjectured Fermat's little theorem, a basic result in modular arithmetic, and Fermat's Last Theorem, as well as proved Fermat's right triangle theorem.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] He also studied prime numbers, the four-square theorem, and Pell's equations.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] The interest of Leonhard Euler (1707–1783) in number theory was first spurred in 1729, when a friend of his, the amateur Christian Goldbach, pointed him towards some of Fermat's work on the subject.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] This has been called the "rebirth" of modern number theory, after Fermat's relative lack of success in getting his contemporaries' attention for the subject.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] He proved Fermat's assertions, including Fermat's little theorem; made initial work towards a proof that every integer is the sum of four squares; and specific cases of Fermat's Last Theorem.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] He wrote on the link between continued fractions and Pell's equation.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] He made the first steps towards analytic number theory.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Three European contemporaries continued the work in elementary number theory.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Joseph-Louis Lagrange (1736–1813) gave full proofs of the four-square theorem, Wilson's theorem, and developed the basic theory of Pell's equations.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Adrien-Marie Legendre (1752–1833) stated the law of quadratic reciprocity.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] He also conjectured what amounts to the prime number theorem and Dirichlet's theorem on arithmetic progressions.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] In his old age, he was the first to prove Fermat's Last Theorem for $n=5$ .
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Carl Friedrich Gauss (1777–1855) wrote *Disquisitiones Arithmeticae* (1801), which had an immense influence in the area of number theory and set its agenda for much of the 19th century.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Gauss proved in this work the law of quadratic reciprocity and developed the theory of quadratic forms.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] He also introduced some basic notation to congruences and devoted a section to computational matters, including primality tests.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] He established a link between roots of unity and number theory.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] In this way, Gauss arguably made forays towards Évariste Galois's work and the area algebraic number theory.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Algebraic number theory may be said to start with the study of reciprocity and cyclotomy, but truly came into its own with the development of abstract algebra and early ideal theory and valuation theory; see below.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] A conventional starting point for analytic number theory is Dirichlet's theorem on arithmetic progressions (1837), whose proof introduced L-functions and involved some asymptotic analysis and a limiting process on a real variable.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] The first use of analytic ideas in number theory actually goes back to Euler (1730s), who used formal power series and non-rigorous (or implicit) limiting arguments.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] The American Mathematical Society awards the *Cole Prize in Number Theory*.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Moreover, number theory is one of the three mathematical subdisciplines rewarded by the *Fermat Prize*.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Elementary number theory deals with the topics in number theory by means of basic methods in arithmetic.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Its primary subjects of study are divisibility, factorization, and primality, as well as congruences in modular arithmetic.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Other topics in elementary number theory include Diophantine equations, continued fractions, integer partitions, and Diophantine approximations.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Arithmetic is the study of numerical operations and investigates how numbers are combined and transformed using the arithmetic operations of addition, subtraction, multiplication, division, exponentiation, extraction of roots, and logarithms.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Multiplication, for instance, is an operation that combines two numbers, referred to as factors, to form a single number, termed the product, such as $2\times 3=6$ .
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Divisibility is a property between two nonzero integers related to division.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] An integer a is said to be divisible by a nonzero integer b if a is a multiple of b ; that is, if there exists an integer q such that $a=bq$ .
[src:number-theory/number-theory] An equivalent formulation is that b divides a and is denoted by a vertical bar, which in this case is $b|a$ .
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Conversely, if this were not the case, then a would not be divided evenly by b , resulting in a remainder.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Euclid's division lemma asserts that a and b can generally be written as $a=bq+r$ , where the remainder r accounts for the smallest positive leftover quantity.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Elementary number theory studies divisibility rules in order to quickly identify if a given integer is divisible by a fixed divisor.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] For instance, it is known that any integer is divisible by 3 if its decimal digit sum is divisible by 3.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] A common divisor of several nonzero integers is an integer that divides all of them.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] The greatest common divisor (gcd) is the largest of such divisors.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Two integers are said to be coprime or relatively prime to one another if their greatest common divisor, and simultaneously their only divisor, is 1 .
[src:number-theory/number-theory] The Euclidean algorithm computes the greatest common divisor of two integers $a,b$ by means of repeatedly applying the division lemma and shifting the divisor and remainder after every step.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] The algorithm can be extended to solve a special case of linear Diophantine equations $ax+by=1$ .
[src:number-theory/number-theory] A Diophantine equation has several unknowns and integer coefficients.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Another kind of Diophantine equation is described in the Pythagorean theorem, $x^{2}+y^{2}=z^{2}$ , whose solutions are called Pythagorean triples if they are all integers.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Another kind of expression is the continued fraction, which writes a sum of an integer and a fraction whose denominator is another such sum.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Elementary number theory studies the divisibility properties of integers such as parity (even and odd numbers), prime numbers, and perfect numbers.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Important number-theoretic functions include the divisor-counting function, the divisor summatory function and its modifications, and Euler's totient function.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] A prime number is an integer greater than 1 whose only positive divisors are 1 and the prime itself.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] A positive integer greater than 1 that is not prime is called a composite number.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Euclid's theorem demonstrates that there are infinitely many prime numbers that comprise the set $\{2,3,5,7,11,\cdots \}$ .
[src:number-theory/number-theory] The sieve of Eratosthenes was devised as an efficient algorithm for identifying all primes up to a given natural number by eliminating all composite numbers.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Factorization is a method of expressing a number as a product.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Specifically in number theory, integer factorization is the decomposition of an integer into a product of integers.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] The process of repeatedly applying this procedure until all factors are prime is known as prime factorization.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] A fundamental property of primes is shown in Euclid's lemma.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] It is a consequence of the lemma that if a prime divides a product of integers, then that prime divides at least one of the factors in the product.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] The unique factorization theorem is the fundamental theorem of arithmetic that relates to prime factorization.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] The theorem states that every integer greater than 1 can be factorised into a product of prime numbers and that this factorisation is unique up to the order of the factors.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] For example, $120$ is expressed uniquely as $2\times 2\times 2\times 3\times 5$ or simply $2^{3}\times 3\times 5$ .
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Modular arithmetic works with finite sets of integers and introduces the concepts of congruence and residue classes.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] A congruence of two integers $a,b$ modulo n (a positive integer called the modulus) is an equivalence relation whereby $n|(a-b)$ is true.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Performing Euclidean division on both a and n , and on b and n , yields the same remainder.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] This written as ${\textstyle a\equiv b{\pmod {n}}}$ .
[src:number-theory/number-theory] In a manner analogous to the 12-hour clock, the sum of 4 and 9 is equal to $13$ , yet congruent to 1 .
[src:number-theory/number-theory] A residue class modulo n is a set that contains all integers congruent to a specified r modulo n .
[src:number-theory/number-theory] For example, $6\mathbb {Z} +1$ contains all multiples of 6 incremented by 1 .
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Modular arithmetic provides a range of formulas for rapidly solving congruences of very large powers.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] An influential theorem is Fermat's little theorem, which states that if a prime p is coprime to some integer a , then ${\textstyle a^{p-1}\equiv 1{\pmod {p}}}$ is true.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Euler's theorem extends this to assert that every integer n satisfies the congruence $a^{\varphi (n)}\equiv 1{\pmod {n}},$ where Euler's totient function $\varphi$ counts all positive integers up to n that are coprime to n .
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Modular arithmetic also provides formulas that are used to solve congruences with unknowns in a similar vein to equation solving in algebra, such as the Chinese remainder theorem.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Analytic number theory, in contrast to elementary number theory, relies on complex numbers and techniques from analysis and calculus.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] It studies the distribution of primes, behavior of number-theoretic functions, and irrational numbers.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Number theory has the reputation of being a field many of whose results can be stated to the layperson.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] At the same time, many of the proofs of these results are not particularly accessible, in part because the range of tools they use is, if anything, unusually broad within mathematics.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] The following are examples of problems in analytic number theory: the prime number theorem, the Goldbach conjecture, the twin prime conjecture, the Hardy–Littlewood conjectures, the Waring problem and the Riemann hypothesis.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Some of the most important tools of analytic number theory are the circle method, sieve methods and L-functions (or, rather, the study of their properties).
[src:number-theory/number-theory] The theory of modular forms (and, more generally, automorphic forms) also occupies an increasingly central place in the toolbox of analytic number theory.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Analysis is the branch of mathematics that studies the limit, defined as the value to which a sequence or function tends as the argument (or index) approaches a specific value.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] In the context of functions, the limit of ${\textstyle {\frac {1}{x}}}$ as x approaches infinity is 0 .
[src:number-theory/number-theory] The complex numbers extend the real numbers with the imaginary unit i defined as the solution to $i^{2}=-1$ .
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Every complex number can be expressed as $x+iy$ , where x is called the real part and y is called the imaginary part.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] The distribution of primes, described by the function $\pi$ that counts all primes up to a given real number, is unpredictable and is a major subject of study in number theory.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Elementary formulas for a partial sequence of primes, including Euler's prime-generating polynomials have been developed.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] However, these cease to function as the primes become too large.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] The prime number theorem in analytic number theory provides a formalisation of the notion that prime numbers appear less commonly as their numerical value increases.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] One distribution states, informally, that the function ${\frac {x}{\log(x)}}$ approximates $\pi (x)$ .
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Another distribution involves an offset logarithmic integral which converges to $\pi (x)$ more quickly.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] The zeta function has been demonstrated to be connected to the distribution of primes.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] He established a connection between the nontrivial zeroes and the prime-counting function.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] In what is now recognised as the unsolved Riemann hypothesis, a solution to it would imply direct consequences for understanding the distribution of primes.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] One may ask analytic questions about algebraic numbers, and use analytic means to answer such questions; it is thus that algebraic and analytic number theory intersect.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] For example, one may define prime ideals (generalizations of prime numbers in the field of algebraic numbers) and ask how many prime ideals there are up to a certain size.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] This question can be answered by means of an examination of Dedekind zeta functions, which are generalizations of the Riemann zeta function, a key analytic object at the roots of the subject.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] This is an example of a general procedure in analytic number theory: deriving information about the distribution of a sequence (here, prime ideals or prime numbers) from the analytic behavior of an appropriately constructed complex-valued function.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Elementary number theory works with *elementary proofs*, a term that excludes the use of complex numbers but may include basic analysis.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] For example, the prime number theorem was first proven using complex analysis in 1896, but an elementary proof was found only in 1949 by Erdős and Selberg.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] For example, proofs based on complex Tauberian theorems, such as Wiener–Ikehara, are often seen as quite enlightening but not elementary despite using Fourier analysis, not complex analysis.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Here as elsewhere, an *elementary* proof may be longer and more difficult for most readers than a more advanced proof.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Some subjects generally considered to be part of analytic number theory (e.g., sieve theory) are better covered by the second rather than the first definition.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Small sieves, for instance, use little analysis and yet still belong to analytic number theory.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] An *algebraic number* is any complex number that is a solution to some polynomial equation $f(x)=0$ with rational coefficients; for example, every solution x of $x^{5}+(11/2)x^{3}-7x^{2}+9=0$ is an algebraic number.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Fields of algebraic numbers are also called *algebraic number fields*, or shortly *number fields*.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Algebraic number theory studies algebraic number fields.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] It could be argued that the simplest kind of number fields, namely quadratic fields, were already studied by Gauss, as the discussion of quadratic forms in *Disquisitiones Arithmeticae* can be restated in terms of ideals and norms in quadratic fields.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] However, neither Bhāskara nor Gauss knew of number fields as such.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] The grounds of the subject were set in the late nineteenth century, when *ideal numbers*, the *theory of ideals* and *valuation theory* were introduced; these are three complementary ways of dealing with the lack of unique factorization in algebraic number fields.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Number fields are often studied as extensions of smaller number fields: a field *L* is said to be an *extension* of a field *K* if *L* contains *K*.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] (For example, the complex numbers *C* are an extension of the reals *R*, and the reals *R* are an extension of the rationals *Q*.) Classifying the possible extensions of a given number field is a difficult and partially open problem.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Abelian extensions—that is, extensions *L* of *K* such that the Galois group Gal(*L*/*K*) of *L* over *K* is an abelian group—are relatively well understood.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Their classification was the object of the programme of class field theory, which was initiated in the late nineteenth century (partly by Kronecker and Eisenstein) and carried out largely in 1900–1950.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] An example of an active area of research in algebraic number theory is Iwasawa theory.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] The Langlands program, one of the main current large-scale research plans in mathematics, is sometimes described as an attempt to generalise class field theory to non-abelian extensions of number fields.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] The central problem of Diophantine geometry is to determine when a Diophantine equation has integer or rational solutions, and if it does, how many.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] The approach taken is to think of the solutions of an equation as a geometric object.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] For example, an equation in two variables defines a curve in the plane.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] More generally, an equation or system of equations in two or more variables defines a curve, a surface, or some other such object in *n*-dimensional space.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] In Diophantine geometry, one asks whether there are any *rational points* (points all of whose coordinates are rationals) or *integral points* (points all of whose coordinates are integers) on the curve or surface.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] If there are any such points, the next step is to ask how many there are and how they are distributed.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] A basic question in this direction is whether there are finitely or infinitely many rational points on a given curve or surface.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Consider, for instance, the Pythagorean equation $x^{2}+y^{2}=1$ .
[src:number-theory/number-theory] One would like to know its rational solutions, namely $(x,y)$ such that *x* and *y* are both rational.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] This is the same as asking for all integer solutions to $a^{2}+b^{2}=c^{2}$ ; any solution to the latter equation gives us a solution $x=a/c$ , $y=b/c$ to the former.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] It is also the same as asking for all points with rational coordinates on the curve described by $x^{2}+y^{2}=1$ (a circle of radius 1 centered on the origin).
[src:number-theory/number-theory] The rephrasing of questions on equations in terms of points on curves is felicitous.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] The finiteness or not of the number of rational or integer points on an algebraic curve (that is, rational or integer solutions to an equation $f(x,y)=0$ , where f is a polynomial in two variables) depends crucially on the genus of the curve.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] A major achievement of this approach is Wiles's proof of Fermat's Last Theorem, for which other geometrical notions are just as crucial.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] There is also the closely linked area of Diophantine approximations: given a number x , determine how well it can be approximated by rational numbers.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] One seeks approximations that are good relative to the amount of space required to write the rational number: call $a/q$ (with $\gcd(a,q)=1$ ) a good approximation to x if $|x-a/q|<{\frac {1}{q^{c}}}$ , where c is large.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] This question is of special interest if x is an algebraic number.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] If x cannot be approximated well, then some equations do not have integer or rational solutions.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Moreover, several concepts (especially that of height) are critical both in Diophantine geometry and in the study of Diophantine approximations.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] This question is also of special interest in transcendental number theory: if a number can be approximated better than any algebraic number, then it is a transcendental number.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] It is by this argument that π and e have been shown to be transcendental.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Diophantine geometry should not be confused with the geometry of numbers, which is a collection of graphical methods for answering certain questions in algebraic number theory.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Arithmetic geometry is a contemporary term for the same domain covered by Diophantine geometry, particularly when one wishes to emphasize the connections to modern algebraic geometry (for example, in Faltings' theorem) rather than to techniques in Diophantine approximations.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Probabilistic number theory starts with questions such as the following: Take an integer n at random between one and a million.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] (this is just another way of asking how many primes there are between one and a million).
[src:number-theory/number-theory] How many prime divisors will n have on average?
[src:number-theory/number-theory] What is the probability that it will have many more or many fewer divisors or prime divisors than the average?
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Should it be possible to write large integers as sums of elements of A ?
[src:number-theory/number-theory] There are two main questions: "Can this be computed?" and "Can it be computed rapidly?" Anyone can test whether a number is prime or, if it is not, split it into prime factors; doing so rapidly is another matter.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Fast algorithms for testing primality are now known, but, in spite of much work (both theoretical and practical), no truly fast algorithm for factoring.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] For a long time, number theory in general, and the study of prime numbers in particular, was seen as the canonical example of pure mathematics, with no applications outside of mathematics other than the use of prime numbered gear teeth to distribute wear evenly.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] In particular, number theorists such as British mathematician G.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Hardy prided themselves on doing work that had absolutely no military significance.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] The number-theorist Leonard Dickson (1874–1954) said "Thank God that number theory is unsullied by any application".
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Such a view is no longer applicable to number theory.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] This vision of the purity of number theory was shattered in the 1970s, when it was publicly announced that prime numbers could be used as the basis for the creation of public-key cryptography algorithms.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Schemes such as RSA are based on the difficulty of factoring large composite numbers into their prime factors.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] These applications have led to significant study of algorithms for computing with prime numbers, and in particular of primality testing, methods for determining whether a given number is prime.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Prime numbers are also used in computing for checksums, hash tables, and pseudorandom number generators.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] In 1974, Donald Knuth said "virtually every theorem in elementary number theory arises in a natural, motivated way in connection with the problem of making computers do high-speed numerical calculations".
[src:number-theory/number-theory] Elementary number theory is taught in discrete mathematics courses for computer scientists.
[src:number-theory/number-theory] It also has applications to the continuous in numerical analysis.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] A **prime number** (or a **prime**) is a natural number greater than 1 that is not a product of two smaller natural numbers.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] A natural number greater than 1 that is not prime is called a composite number.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] For example, 5 is prime because the only ways of writing it as a product, 1 × 5 or 5 × 1, involve 5 itself.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] However, 4 is composite because it is a product (2 × 2) in which both numbers are smaller than 4.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Primes are central in number theory because of the fundamental theorem of arithmetic: every natural number greater than 1 is either a prime itself or can be factorized as a product of primes that is unique up to their order.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] The property of being prime is called **primality**.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] A simple but slow method of checking the primality of a given number ⁠ n ⁠, called trial division, tests whether ⁠ n ⁠ is a multiple of any integer between 2 and ⁠ ${\sqrt {n}}$ ⁠.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Faster algorithms include the Miller–Rabin primality test, which is fast but has a small chance of error, and the AKS primality test, which always produces the correct answer in polynomial time but is too slow to be practical.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Particularly fast methods are available for numbers of special forms, such as Mersenne numbers, and these have been used to find large prime numbers.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] There are infinitely many primes, as demonstrated by Euclid around 300 BC.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] No known simple formula separates prime numbers from composite numbers.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] However, the distribution of primes within the natural numbers in the large can be statistically modelled.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] The first result in that direction is the prime number theorem, proven at the end of the 19th century, which says roughly that the probability of a randomly chosen large number being prime is inversely proportional to its number of digits, that is, to its logarithm.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Several historical questions regarding prime numbers are still unsolved.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] These include Goldbach's conjecture, that every even integer greater than 2 can be expressed as the sum of two primes, and the twin prime conjecture, that there are infinitely many pairs of primes that differ by two.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Such questions spurred the development of various branches of number theory, focusing on analytic or algebraic aspects of numbers.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Primes are used in several routines in information technology, such as public-key cryptography, which relies on the difficulty of factoring large numbers into their prime factors.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] In abstract algebra, objects that behave in a generalized way like prime numbers include prime elements and prime ideals.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] A natural number (1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, etc.) is called a *prime number* (or a *prime*) if it is greater than 1 and cannot be written as the product of two smaller natural numbers.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] The numbers greater than 1 that are not prime are called composite numbers.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] In other words, ⁠ n ⁠ is prime if ⁠ n ⁠ items cannot be divided up into smaller equal-size groups of more than one item, or if it is not possible to arrange ⁠ n ⁠ dots into a rectangular grid that is more than one dot wide and more than one dot high.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] For example, among the numbers 1 through 6, the numbers 2, 3, and 5 are the prime numbers, as there are no other numbers that divide them evenly (without a remainder).
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] 1 is not prime, as it is specifically excluded in the definition.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] 4 = 2 × 2 and 6 = 2 × 3 are both composite.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] The divisors of a natural number ⁠ n ⁠ are the natural numbers that divide ⁠ n ⁠ evenly.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Every natural number has both 1 and itself as a divisor.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] If it has any other divisor, it cannot be prime.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] This leads to an equivalent definition of prime numbers: they are the numbers with exactly two positive divisors.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] As 1 has only one divisor, itself, it is not prime by this definition.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Yet another way to express the same thing is that a number ⁠ n ⁠ is prime if it is greater than one and if none of the numbers $2,3,\dots ,n-1$ divides ⁠ n ⁠ evenly.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] No even number ⁠ n ⁠ greater than 2 is prime because any such number can be expressed as the product ⁠ $2\times n/2$ ⁠.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Therefore, every prime number other than 2 is an odd number, and is called an *odd prime*.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Similarly, when written in the usual decimal system, all prime numbers larger than 5 end in 1, 3, 7, or 9.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] The numbers that end with other digits are all composite: decimal numbers that end in 0, 2, 4, 6, or 8 are even, and decimal numbers that end in 0 or 5 are divisible by 5.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] The set of all primes is sometimes denoted by $\mathbf {P}$ (a boldface capital P) or by $\mathbb {P}$ (a blackboard bold capital P).
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] From around 1550 BC, the Rhind Mathematical Papyrus has Egyptian fraction expansions of different forms for fractions with prime and composite denominators.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] However, the earliest surviving records of the study of prime numbers come from the ancient Greek mathematicians, who called them *prōtos arithmòs* (πρῶτος ἀριθμὸς).
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] 300 BC) proves the infinitude of primes and the fundamental theorem of arithmetic, and shows how to construct a perfect number from a Mersenne prime.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Another Greek invention, the Sieve of Eratosthenes, is still used to construct lists of primes.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Around 1000 AD, the Islamic mathematician Ibn al-Haytham (Alhazen) found Wilson's theorem, characterizing the prime numbers as the numbers ⁠ n ⁠ that evenly divide ⁠ $(n-1)!+1$ ⁠.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] He also conjectured that all even perfect numbers come from Euclid's construction using Mersenne primes, but was unable to prove it.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Another Islamic mathematician, Ibn al-Banna' al-Marrakushi, observed that the sieve of Eratosthenes can be sped up by considering only the prime divisors up to the square root of the upper limit.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Fibonacci took the innovations from Islamic mathematics to Europe.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] His book *Liber Abaci* (1202) was the first to describe trial division for testing primality, again using divisors only up to the square root.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] In 1640 Pierre de Fermat stated (without proof) Fermat's little theorem (later proved by Leibniz and Euler).
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Fermat also investigated the primality of the Fermat numbers ⁠ $2^{2^{n}}+1$ ⁠, and Marin Mersenne studied the Mersenne primes, prime numbers of the form $2^{p}-1$ with ⁠ p ⁠ itself a prime.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Christian Goldbach formulated Goldbach's conjecture, that every even number is the sum of two primes, in a 1742 letter to Euler.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Euler proved Alhazen's conjecture (now the Euclid–Euler theorem) that all even perfect numbers can be constructed from Mersenne primes.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] He introduced methods from mathematical analysis to this area in his proofs of the infinitude of the primes and the divergence of the sum of the reciprocals of the primes ⁠ ${\tfrac {1}{2}}+{\tfrac {1}{3}}+{\tfrac {1}{5}}+{\tfrac {1}{7}}+{\tfrac {1}{11}}+\cdots$ ⁠.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] At the start of the 19th century, Legendre and Gauss conjectured that as ⁠ x ⁠ tends to infinity, the number of primes up to ⁠ x ⁠ is asymptotic to ⁠ $x/\log x$ ⁠, where $\log x$ is the natural logarithm of ⁠ x ⁠.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] A weaker consequence of this high density of primes was Bertrand's postulate, that for every $n>1$ there is a prime between ⁠ n ⁠ and ⁠ $2n$ ⁠, proved in 1852 by Pafnuty Chebyshev.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Ideas of Bernhard Riemann in his 1859 paper on the zeta-function sketched an outline for proving the conjecture of Legendre and Gauss.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Although the closely related Riemann hypothesis remains unproven, Riemann's outline was completed in 1896 by Hadamard and de la Vallée Poussin, and the result is now known as the prime number theorem.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Another important 19th century result was Dirichlet's theorem on arithmetic progressions, that certain arithmetic progressions contain infinitely many primes.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Many mathematicians have worked on primality tests for numbers larger than those where trial division is practicably applicable.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Methods that are restricted to specific number forms include Pépin's test for Fermat numbers (1877), Proth's theorem (c.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] 1878), the Lucas–Lehmer primality test (originated 1856), and the generalized Lucas primality test.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Since 1951 all the largest known primes have been found using these tests on computers.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] The search for ever larger primes has generated interest outside mathematical circles, through the Great Internet Mersenne Prime Search and other distributed computing projects.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] The idea that prime numbers had few applications outside of pure mathematics was shattered in the 1970s when public-key cryptography and the RSA cryptosystem were invented, using prime numbers as their basis.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] The increased practical importance of computerized primality testing and factorization led to the development of improved methods capable of handling large numbers of unrestricted form.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] The mathematical theory of prime numbers also moved forward with the Green–Tao theorem (2004) that there are arbitrarily long arithmetic progressions of prime numbers, and Yitang Zhang's 2013 proof that there exist infinitely many prime gaps of bounded size.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Most early Greeks did not even consider 1 to be a number, so they could not consider its primality.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] A few scholars in the Greek and later Roman tradition, including Nicomachus, Iamblichus, Boethius, and Cassiodorus, also considered the prime numbers to be a subdivision of the odd numbers, so they did not consider ⁠ 2 ⁠ to be prime either.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] However, Euclid and a majority of the other Greek mathematicians considered ⁠ 2 ⁠ as prime.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] The medieval Islamic mathematicians largely followed the Greeks in viewing 1 as not being a number.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] By the Middle Ages and Renaissance, mathematicians began treating 1 as a number, and by the 17th century some of them included it as the first prime number.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] In the mid-18th century, Christian Goldbach listed 1 as prime in his correspondence with Leonhard Euler; however, Euler himself did not consider 1 to be prime.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Many 19th century mathematicians still considered 1 to be prime, and Derrick Norman Lehmer included 1 in his *list of primes less than ten million* published in 1914.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Lists of primes that included 1 continued to be published as recently as 1956.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] However, by the early 20th century mathematicians began to agree that 1 should not be listed as prime, but rather in its own special category as a "unit".
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] If 1 were to be considered a prime, many statements involving primes would need to be awkwardly reworded.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] For example, the fundamental theorem of arithmetic would need to be rephrased in terms of factorizations into primes greater than 1, because every number would have multiple factorizations with any number of copies of 1.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Similarly, the sieve of Eratosthenes would not work correctly if it handled 1 as a prime, because it would eliminate all multiples of 1 (that is, all other numbers) and output only the single number 1.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Some other more technical properties of prime numbers also do not hold for the number 1: for instance, the formulas for Euler's totient function or for the sum of divisors function are different for prime numbers than they are for 1.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Writing a number as a product of prime numbers is called a *prime factorization* of the number.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] The terms in the product are called *prime factors*.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] The central importance of prime numbers to number theory and mathematics in general stems from the *fundamental theorem of arithmetic*.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] This theorem states that every integer larger than 1 can be written as a product of one or more primes.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] More strongly, this product is unique in the sense that any two prime factorizations of the same number will have the same numbers of copies of the same primes, although their ordering may differ.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] So, although there are many different ways of finding a factorization using an integer factorization algorithm, they all must produce the same result.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Primes can thus be considered the "basic building blocks" of the natural numbers.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Some proofs of the uniqueness of prime factorizations are based on Euclid's lemma: If ⁠ p ⁠ is a prime number and ⁠ p ⁠ divides a product $ab$ of integers ⁠ a ⁠ and $b,$ then ⁠ p ⁠ divides ⁠ a ⁠ or ⁠ p ⁠ divides ⁠ b ⁠ (or both).
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Conversely, if a number ⁠ p ⁠ has the property that when it divides a product it always divides at least one factor of the product, then ⁠ p ⁠ must be prime.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] There are infinitely many prime numbers.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] This statement is referred to as *Euclid's theorem* in honor of the ancient Greek mathematician Euclid, since the first known proof for this statement is attributed to him.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Many more proofs of the infinitude of primes are known, including an analytical proof by Euler, Goldbach's proof based on Fermat numbers, Furstenberg's proof using general topology, and Kummer's proof by contradiction.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Euclid's proof shows that every finite list of primes is incomplete.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] with one or more prime factors. ⁠ N ⁠ is evenly divisible by each of these factors, but ⁠ N ⁠ has a remainder of one when divided by any of the prime numbers in the given list, so none of the prime factors of ⁠ N ⁠ can be in the given list.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Because there is no finite list of all the primes, there must be infinitely many primes.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] The numbers formed by adding one to the products of the smallest primes are called Euclid numbers.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] There is no known efficient formula for primes.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] For example, there is no non-constant polynomial, even in several variables, that takes only prime values.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] However, there are numerous expressions that do encode all primes, or only primes.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] One possible formula is based on Wilson's theorem and generates the number 2 many times and all other primes exactly once.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] There is also a set of Diophantine equations in nine variables and one parameter with the following property: the parameter is prime if and only if the resulting system of equations has a solution over the natural numbers.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] This can be used to obtain a single formula with the property that all its positive values are prime.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Other examples of prime-generating formulas come from Mills' theorem and a theorem of Wright.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] are prime for any natural number ⁠ n ⁠ in the first formula, and any number of exponents in the second formula.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Here $\lfloor {}\cdot {}\rfloor$ represents the floor function, the largest integer less than or equal to the number in question.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Many conjectures revolving about primes have been posed.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Often having an elementary formulation, many of these conjectures have withstood proof for decades: all four of Landau's problems from 1912 are still unsolved.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] One of them is Goldbach's conjecture, which asserts that every even integer ⁠ n ⁠ greater than ⁠ 2 ⁠ can be written as a sum of two primes.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] As of 2014, this conjecture has been verified for all numbers up to $n=4\cdot 10^{18}.$ Weaker statements than this have been proven; for example, Vinogradov's theorem says that every sufficiently large odd integer can be written as a sum of three primes.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Chen's theorem says that every sufficiently large even number can be expressed as the sum of a prime and a semiprime (the product of two primes).
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Also, any even integer greater than 10 can be written as the sum of six primes.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] The branch of number theory studying such questions is called additive number theory.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Another type of problem concerns prime gaps, the differences between consecutive primes.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] The existence of arbitrarily large prime gaps can be seen by noting that the sequence $n!+2,n!+3,\dots ,n!+n$ consists of $n-1$ composite numbers, for any natural number $n.$ However, large prime gaps occur much earlier than this argument shows.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] For example, the first prime gap of length 8 is between the primes 89 and 97, much smaller than $8!=40320.$ It is conjectured that there are infinitely many twin primes, pairs of primes with difference 2; this is the twin prime conjecture.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Prime gaps can be generalized to prime ⁠ k ⁠-tuples, patterns in the differences among more than two prime numbers.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Their infinitude and density are the subject of the first Hardy–Littlewood conjecture, which can be motivated by the heuristic that the prime numbers behave similarly to a random sequence of numbers with density given by the prime number theorem.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Analytic number theory studies number theory through the lens of continuous functions, limits, infinite series, and the related mathematics of the infinite and infinitesimal.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] This area of study began with Leonhard Euler and his first major result, the solution to the Basel problem.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] The problem asked for the value of the infinite sum $1+{\tfrac {1}{4}}+{\tfrac {1}{9}}+{\tfrac {1}{16}}+\dots ,$ which today can be recognized as the value $\zeta (2)$ of the Riemann zeta function.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] This function is closely connected to the prime numbers and to one of the most significant unsolved problems in mathematics, the Riemann hypothesis.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] The reciprocal of this number, ⁠ $6/\pi ^{2}$ ⁠, is the limiting probability that two random numbers selected uniformly from a large range are relatively prime (have no factors in common).
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] The distribution of primes in the large, such as the question how many primes are smaller than a given, large threshold, is described by the prime number theorem, but no efficient formula for the ⁠ n ⁠-th prime is known.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] with relatively prime integers ⁠ a ⁠ and ⁠ b ⁠ take infinitely many prime values.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Although conjectures have been formulated about the proportions of primes in higher-degree polynomials, they remain unproven, and it is unknown whether there exists a quadratic polynomial that (for integer arguments) is prime infinitely often.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Euler showed that, for any arbitrary real number ⁠ x ⁠, there exists a prime ⁠ p ⁠ for which this sum is greater than ⁠ x ⁠.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] This shows that there are infinitely many primes, because if there were finitely many primes the sum would reach its maximum value at the biggest prime rather than growing past every ⁠ x ⁠.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] The growth rate of this sum is described more precisely by Mertens' second theorem.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] does not grow to infinity as ⁠ n ⁠ goes to infinity (see the Basel problem).
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] In this sense, prime numbers occur more often than squares of natural numbers, although both sets are infinite.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Because of Brun's theorem, it is not possible to use Euler's method to solve the twin prime conjecture, that there exist infinitely many twin primes.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] The prime-counting function $\pi (n)$ is defined as the number of primes not greater than ⁠ n ⁠.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] For example, ⁠ $\pi (11)=5$ ⁠, since there are five primes less than or equal to 11.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Methods such as the Meissel–Lehmer algorithm can compute exact values of $\pi (n)$ faster than it would be possible to list each prime up to ⁠ n ⁠.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] and means that the ratio of $\pi (n)$ to the right-hand fraction approaches 1 as ⁠ n ⁠ grows to infinity.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] This implies that the likelihood that a randomly chosen number less than ⁠ n ⁠ is prime is (approximately) inversely proportional to the number of digits in ⁠ n ⁠.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] It also implies that the ⁠ n ⁠th prime number is proportional to $n\log n$ and therefore that the average size of a prime gap is proportional to ⁠ $\log n$ ⁠.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] An arithmetic progression is a finite or infinite sequence of numbers such that consecutive numbers in the sequence all have the same difference.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] This difference is called the modulus of the progression.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] is an infinite arithmetic progression with modulus 9.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] In an arithmetic progression, all the numbers have the same remainder when divided by the modulus; in this example, the remainder is 3.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Because both the modulus 9 and the remainder 3 are multiples of 3, so is every element in the sequence.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Therefore, this progression contains only one prime number, 3 itself.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] can have more than one prime only when its remainder ⁠ a ⁠ and modulus ⁠ q ⁠ are relatively prime.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] If they are relatively prime, Dirichlet's theorem on arithmetic progressions asserts that the progression contains infinitely many primes.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Primes in the arithmetic progressions modulo 9.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Each row of the thin horizontal band shows one of the nine possible progressions mod 9, with prime numbers marked in red.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] The progressions of numbers that are 0, 3, or 6 mod 9 contain at most one prime number (the number 3); the remaining progressions of numbers that are 1, 2, 4, 5, 7, and 8 mod 9 have infinitely many prime numbers, with similar numbers of primes in each progression.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] The Green–Tao theorem shows that there are arbitrarily long finite arithmetic progressions consisting only of primes.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] yields prime numbers for ⁠ $1\leq n\leq 40$ ⁠, although composite numbers appear among its later values.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] The search for an explanation for this phenomenon led to the deep algebraic number theory of Heegner numbers and the class number problem.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] The Hardy–Littlewood conjecture F predicts the density of primes among the values of quadratic polynomials with integer coefficients in terms of the logarithmic integral and the polynomial coefficients.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] No quadratic polynomial has been proven to take infinitely many prime values.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] The Ulam spiral arranges the natural numbers in a two-dimensional grid, spiraling in concentric squares surrounding the origin with the prime numbers highlighted.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Visually, the primes appear to cluster on certain diagonals and not others, suggesting that some quadratic polynomials take prime values more often than others.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Russian mathematician Viktor Bunyakovsky in 1857 conjectured that any one-variable polynomial $f(x)$ with integer coefficients would produce infinitely many primes in the sequence $f(1),f(2),f(3),\dots$ .
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] A polynomial must meet the conditions that its leading coefficient is positive, it is irreducible over the rationals, and the value of such a sequence has no common factor larger than 1.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] This conjecture was generalized by Polish mathematician Andrzej Schinzel's hypothesis H, and later extended to multivariable polynomials in Dickson's conjecture and then Bateman–Horn conjecture.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] One of the most famous unsolved questions in mathematics, dating from 1859, and one of the Millennium Prize Problems, is the Riemann hypothesis, which asks where the zeros of the Riemann zeta function $\zeta (s)$ are located.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] This function is an analytic function on the complex numbers.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] The Euler product can be derived from the fundamental theorem of arithmetic, and shows the close connection between the zeta function and the prime numbers.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] The Riemann hypothesis states that the zeros of the zeta-function are all either negative even numbers, or complex numbers with real part equal to 1/2.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] The original proof of the prime number theorem was based on a weak form of this hypothesis, that there are no zeros with real part equal to 1, although other more elementary proofs have been found.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] The prime-counting function can be expressed by Riemann's explicit formula as a sum in which each term comes from one of the zeros of the zeta function; the main term of this sum is the logarithmic integral, and the remaining terms cause the sum to fluctuate above and below the main term.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] In this sense, the zeros control how regularly the prime numbers are distributed.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] If the Riemann hypothesis is true, these fluctuations will be small, and the asymptotic distribution of primes given by the prime number theorem will also hold over much shorter intervals (of length about the square root of ⁠ x ⁠ for intervals near a number ⁠ x ⁠).
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Modular arithmetic modifies usual arithmetic by only using the numbers ⁠ $\{0,1,2,\dots ,n-1\}$ ⁠, for a natural number ⁠ n ⁠ called the modulus.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Any other natural number can be mapped into this system by replacing it by its remainder after division by ⁠ n ⁠.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Modular sums, differences and products are calculated by performing the same replacement by the remainder on the result of the usual sum, difference, or product of integers.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Equality of integers corresponds to *congruence* in modular arithmetic: ⁠ x ⁠ and ⁠ y ⁠ are congruent (written $x\equiv y$ mod ⁠ n ⁠) when they have the same remainder after division by ⁠ n ⁠.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] In this system of numbers, division by all nonzero numbers is possible if and only if the modulus is prime.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] For instance, with the prime number 7 as modulus, division by 3 is possible: ⁠ $2/3\equiv 3{\bmod {7}}$ ⁠, because clearing denominators by multiplying both sides by 3 gives the valid formula ⁠ $2\equiv 9{\bmod {7}}$ ⁠.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] However, with the composite modulus 6, division by 3 is impossible.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] There is no valid solution to $2/3\equiv x{\bmod {6}}$ : clearing denominators by multiplying by 3 causes the left-hand side to become 2 while the right-hand side becomes either 0 or 3.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] In the terminology of abstract algebra, the ability to perform division means that modular arithmetic modulo a prime number forms a field or, more specifically, a finite field, while other moduli only give a ring but not a field.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Several theorems about primes can be formulated using modular arithmetic.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] For instance, Fermat's little theorem states that if $a\not \equiv 0$ (mod ⁠ p ⁠), then $a^{p-1}\equiv 1$ (mod ⁠ p ⁠).
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Giuga's conjecture says that this equation is also a sufficient condition for ⁠ p ⁠ to be prime.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Wilson's theorem says that an integer $p>1$ is prime if and only if the factorial $(p-1)!$ is congruent to $-1$ mod ⁠ p ⁠.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] For a composite number ⁠ $n=r\cdot s$ ⁠ this cannot hold, since one of its factors divides both n and ⁠ $(n-1)!$ ⁠, and so $(n-1)!\equiv -1{\pmod {n}}$ is impossible.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] The ⁠ p ⁠-adic order $\nu _{p}(n)$ of an integer ⁠ n ⁠ is the number of copies of ⁠ p ⁠ in the prime factorization of ⁠ n ⁠.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] The same concept can be extended from integers to rational numbers by defining the ⁠ p ⁠-adic order of a fraction $m/n$ to be ⁠ $\nu _{p}(m)-\nu _{p}(n)$ ⁠.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] The ⁠ p ⁠-adic absolute value $|q|_{p}$ of any rational number ⁠ q ⁠ is then defined as ⁠ $\vert q\vert _{p}=p^{-\nu _{p}(q)}$ ⁠.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Multiplying an integer by its ⁠ p ⁠-adic absolute value cancels out the factors of ⁠ p ⁠ in its factorization, leaving only the other primes.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Just as the distance between two real numbers can be measured by the absolute value of their difference, the distance between two rational numbers can be measured by their ⁠ p ⁠-adic distance, the ⁠ p ⁠-adic absolute value of their difference.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] For this definition of distance, two numbers are close together (they have a small distance) when their difference is divisible by a high power of ⁠ p ⁠.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] In the same way that the real numbers can be formed from the rational numbers and their distances, by adding extra limiting values to form a complete field, the rational numbers with the ⁠ p ⁠-adic distance can be extended to a different complete field, the ⁠ p ⁠-adic numbers.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] The extension from the rational numbers to the real numbers, for instance, is a place in which the distance between numbers is the usual absolute value of their difference.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] The corresponding mapping to an additive group would be the logarithm of the absolute value, although this does not meet all the requirements of a valuation.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] According to Ostrowski's theorem, up to a natural notion of equivalence, the real numbers and ⁠ p ⁠-adic numbers, with their orders and absolute values, are the only valuations, absolute values, and places on the rational numbers.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] The local–global principle allows certain problems over the rational numbers to be solved by piecing together solutions from each of their places, again underlining the importance of primes to number theory.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] A commutative ring is an algebraic structure where addition, subtraction and multiplication are defined.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] The integers are a ring, and the prime numbers in the integers have been generalized to rings in two different ways, *prime elements* and *irreducible elements*.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] An element ⁠ p ⁠ of a ring ⁠ R ⁠ is called prime if it is nonzero, has no multiplicative inverse (that is, it is not a unit), and satisfies the following requirement: whenever ⁠ p ⁠ divides the product $xy$ of two elements of ⁠ R ⁠, it also divides at least one of ⁠ x ⁠ or ⁠ y ⁠.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] An element is irreducible if it is neither a unit nor the product of two other non-unit elements.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] In an arbitrary ring, all prime elements are irreducible.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] The converse does not hold in general, but does hold for unique factorization domains.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] The fundamental theorem of arithmetic continues to hold (by definition) in unique factorization domains.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] An example of such a domain is the Gaussian integers ⁠ $\mathbb {Z} [i]$ ⁠, the ring of complex numbers of the form $a+bi$ where ⁠ i ⁠ denotes the imaginary unit and ⁠ a ⁠ and ⁠ b ⁠ are arbitrary integers.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Its prime elements are known as Gaussian primes.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Not every number that is prime among the integers remains prime in the Gaussian integers; for instance, the number 2 can be written as a product of the two Gaussian primes $1+i$ and ⁠ $1-i$ ⁠.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Rational primes (the prime elements in the integers) congruent to 3 mod 4 are Gaussian primes, but rational primes congruent to 1 mod 4 are not.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] This is a consequence of Fermat's theorem on sums of two squares, which states that an odd prime ⁠ p ⁠ is expressible as the sum of two squares, ⁠ $p=x^{2}+y^{2}$ ⁠, and therefore factorable as ⁠ $p=(x+iy)(x-iy)$ ⁠, exactly when ⁠ p ⁠ is 1 mod 4.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Not every ring is a unique factorization domain.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] For instance, in the ring of numbers $a+b{\sqrt {-5}}$ (for integers ⁠ a ⁠ and ⁠ b ⁠) the number $21$ has two factorizations ⁠ $21=3\cdot 7=(1+2{\sqrt {-5}})(1-2{\sqrt {-5}})$ ⁠, where none of the four factors can be reduced any further, so it does not have a unique factorization.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] In order to extend unique factorization to a larger class of rings, the notion of a number can be replaced with that of an ideal, a subset of the elements of a ring that contains all sums of pairs of its elements, and all products of its elements with ring elements.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] *Prime ideals*, which generalize prime elements in the sense that the principal ideal generated by a prime element is a prime ideal, are an important tool and object of study in commutative algebra, algebraic number theory and algebraic geometry.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] The fundamental theorem of arithmetic generalizes to the Lasker–Noether theorem, which expresses every ideal in a Noetherian commutative ring as an intersection of primary ideals, which are the appropriate generalizations of prime powers.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] The spectrum of a ring is a geometric space whose points are the prime ideals of the ring.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Arithmetic geometry also benefits from this notion, and many concepts exist in both geometry and number theory.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] For example, factorization or ramification of prime ideals when lifted to an extension field, a basic problem of algebraic number theory, bears some resemblance with ramification in geometry.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] These concepts can even assist with in number-theoretic questions solely concerned with integers.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] For example, prime ideals in the ring of integers of quadratic number fields can be used in proving quadratic reciprocity, a statement that concerns the existence of square roots modulo integer prime numbers.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] Early attempts to prove Fermat's Last Theorem led to Kummer's introduction of regular primes, integer prime numbers connected with the failure of unique factorization in the cyclotomic integers.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] The question of how many integer prime numbers factor into a product of multiple prime ideals in an algebraic number field is addressed by Chebotarev's density theorem, which (when applied to the cyclotomic integers) has Dirichlet's theorem on primes in arithmetic progressions as a special case.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] In the theory of finite groups the Sylow theorems imply that, if a power of a prime number $p^{n}$ divides the order of a group, then the group has a subgroup of order ⁠ $p^{n}$ ⁠.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p01] By Lagrange's theorem, any group of prime order is a cyclic group, and by Burnside's theorem any group whose order is divisible by only two primes is solvable.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p02] The most basic primality testing routine, trial division, is too slow to be useful for large numbers.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p02] One group of modern primality tests is applicable to arbitrary numbers, while more efficient tests are available for numbers of special types.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p02] Most primality tests only tell whether their argument is prime or not.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p02] Routines that also provide a prime factor of composite arguments (or all of its prime factors) are called factorization algorithms.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p02] The most basic method of checking the primality of a given integer ⁠ n ⁠ is called *trial division*.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p02] This method divides ⁠ n ⁠ by each integer from 2 up to the square root of ⁠ n ⁠.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p02] Any such integer dividing ⁠ n ⁠ evenly establishes ⁠ n ⁠ as composite; otherwise it is prime.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p02] Integers larger than the square root do not need to be checked because, whenever ⁠ $n=a\cdot b$ ⁠, one of the two factors ⁠ a ⁠ and ⁠ b ⁠ is less than or equal to the square root of ⁠ n ⁠.
[src:number-theory/prime-number-p02] Another optimization is to check only primes as factors in this range.
